@node RFC 000
@chapter RFC 000: Form Copilot Specification


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Historical (superseded by RFC 004)

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-02-05

@noindent
@strong{Superseded:} 2026-02-20 — form-copilot renamed to smrti (RFC 004)

@noindent
@strong{Purpose:} Capture what form-copilot was, how it worked, and why it was built this way


@quotation
@strong{Note:} This RFC documents the original form-copilot architecture.
@end quotation
@quotation
The project was renamed to @strong{smrti} (advaita-smrti) in RFC 004.
@end quotation
@quotation
File references (@code{form_copilot.py}, SQLite-primary storage) reflect
@end quotation
@quotation
the state at time of writing. See RFC 004 for current architecture.
@end quotation



@section What Form Copilot Is

Form Copilot is a collaborative tool for completing multi-section applications and questionnaires. It combines:
@itemize @bullet
@item
A structured question database with priorities and dependencies
@item
An interactive menu system for navigating questions
@item
Claude Code integration for AI-assisted answer drafting
@item
Export capabilities for multiple formats
@end itemize

@noindent
@strong{Core insight:} Complex applications (job applications, grant proposals, business plans) benefit from:

@enumerate
@item
Breaking the work into prioritized questions
@item
Tracking progress across sessions
@item
AI collaboration that maintains context
@item
Exporting polished results
@end enumerate



@section Architecture Overview


@example
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    form_copilot.py                       │
│                   (CLI Entry Point)                      │
│         Commands: interactive, export, validate          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                           │
                           ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                   sea_assistant.py                       │
│                (Interactive Menu UI)                     │
│                                                          │
│  [1] Work on priorities    [5] View progress            │
│  [2] Continue where left   [6] Export answers           │
│  [3] Browse sections       [C] Work with Claude         │
│  [4] Jump to question      [Q] Quit                     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                           │
              ┌────────────┴────────────┐
              ▼                         ▼
┌──────────────────────┐    ┌──────────────────────────┐
│ sea_application_     │    │   Claude Code Session    │
│     helper.py        │    │                          │
│                      │    │  .sea_question_context   │
│  SQLite Database     │    │        ↓                 │
│  - sections          │    │  /form-start             │
│  - questions         │    │  /form-save              │
│  - answers           │    │        ↓                 │
│  - business_dirs     │    │  .sea_answer.md          │
└──────────────────────┘    └──────────────────────────┘
@end example



@section Design Decisions


@subsection D1: SQLite for Answer Storage

@noindent
@strong{Decision:} Store answers in SQLite database per form.


@noindent
@strong{Alternatives considered:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
JSON files (simpler, but no querying)
@item
Markdown files (human-readable, but parsing complex)
@item
Cloud storage (requires connectivity)
@end itemize

@noindent
@strong{Rationale:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
Structured queries (by section, status, priority)
@item
Transactions prevent corruption
@item
Single file, portable
@item
Python stdlib support (no dependencies)
@end itemize

@strong{Trade-offs accepted:}
@itemize @bullet
@item
Not git-friendly (binary file)
@item
Harder to manually inspect than JSON/Markdown
@item
Per-form databases means no cross-form queries
@end itemize



@subsection D2: JSON Config for Question Structure

@noindent
@strong{Decision:} Define questions, sections, and dependencies in JSON config files.


@noindent
@strong{Alternatives considered:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
YAML (more readable, extra dependency)
@item
Database tables (less portable)
@item
Hardcoded (not reusable)
@end itemize

@noindent
@strong{Rationale:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
JSON Schema validation available
@item
No extra dependencies
@item
Easy to create new forms from examples
@item
Shareable as templates
@end itemize

@noindent
@strong{Schema enforces:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
Required fields (id, question_text, section)
@item
Valid types (text, long_text, yes_no, number, choice)
@item
Priority levels (1-3)
@item
Dependency references (depends_on)
@end itemize



@subsection D3: Subprocess to Claude Code CLI

@noindent
@strong{Decision:} Launch Claude Code as subprocess, communicate via files.


@noindent
@strong{Alternatives considered:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
Claude API directly (more control, more code)
@item
MCP server (async, complex)
@item
Embedded agent (tight coupling)
@end itemize

@noindent
@strong{Rationale:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
Claude Code already exists and works
@item
User stays in familiar Claude Code environment
@item
File-based handoff is simple and debuggable
@item
No API key management in form-copilot
@end itemize

@noindent
@strong{Protocol:} 

@enumerate
@item
Python writes @code{.sea_question_context.json}
@item
Python launches @code{claude} with initial prompt
@item
User works in Claude Code, uses @code{/form-start}, @code{/form-save}
@item
Claude Code writes @code{.sea_answer.md}
@item
Python reads answer, confirms save with user
@item
Python stores in database
@end enumerate

@strong{Trade-offs accepted:}
@itemize @bullet
@item
User must manually exit Claude Code
@item
No background processing
@item
Requires Claude Code installed
@end itemize



@subsection D4: Priority-Based Workflow

@noindent
@strong{Decision:} Questions have priority 1-3. Default workflow starts with priority 1.


@noindent
@strong{Alternatives considered:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
Strict linear order (inflexible)
@item
Dependency-only ordering (complex for users)
@item
No ordering (overwhelming)
@end itemize

@noindent
@strong{Rationale:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
Priority 1 = foundational (answer these first, other answers reference them)
@item
Priority 2 = important (bulk of the application)
@item
Priority 3 = nice-to-have (if time permits)
@item
User can override via section browsing or direct jump
@end itemize



@subsection D5: Session Logging

@noindent
@strong{Decision:} Log events to @code{session_log.json} for analytics and history.


@noindent
@strong{Events tracked:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{claude_session_start} - When user enters Claude collaboration
@item
@code{answer_saved} - When answer committed to database
@item
@code{notes_added} - When user adds notes without full answer
@end itemize

@noindent
@strong{Rationale:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
Understand usage patterns
@item
Track answer evolution over time
@item
Debug issues
@item
Potential for "session replay" feature
@end itemize



@subsection D6: Multiple Export Formats

@noindent
@strong{Decision:} Support JSON, Markdown, Texinfo (→ PDF/HTML).


@noindent
@strong{Rationale:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
JSON: Machine-readable, backup
@item
Markdown: Human-readable, pasteable
@item
Texinfo: Professional typesetting for formal submissions
@end itemize

@noindent
@strong{Why Texinfo over LaTeX:} 

@itemize @bullet
@item
Simpler syntax
@item
Built-in PDF and HTML generation via @code{makeinfo}
@item
Good enough for application documents
@end itemize



@section Component Specifications


@subsection Question Context (@code{.sea_question_context.json})

Written by Python before launching Claude:


@example
@{
  "question_id": "biz_1",
  "question_text": "What problem does your business solve?",
  "helper_text": "Think about the pain point you address...",
  "section": "Business Overview",
  "priority": 1,
  "current_answer": null,
  "notes": "Some rough thoughts...",
  "related_answers": @{
    "biz_2": "We target small business owners..."
  @}
@}
@end example


@subsection Answer Output (@code{.sea_answer.md})

Written by Claude Code, read by Python:


@example
Our business solves the complexity problem in multi-step
applications. Users struggle to maintain context across
dozens of questions spanning multiple sections...
@end example

No headers, no metadata. Just the answer text.


@subsection Database Schema


@example
CREATE TABLE sections (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,
    name TEXT NOT NULL,      -- machine name
    title TEXT NOT NULL,     -- display title
    description TEXT
);

CREATE TABLE questions (
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,     -- e.g., "biz_1"
    section_id INTEGER,
    question_text TEXT NOT NULL,
    question_type TEXT DEFAULT 'text',
    priority INTEGER DEFAULT 3,
    depends_on TEXT,         -- comma-separated question IDs
    helper_text TEXT,
    FOREIGN KEY (section_id) REFERENCES sections(id)
);

CREATE TABLE answers (
    question_id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    answer_text TEXT,
    notes TEXT,              -- user's working notes
    last_updated TEXT,       -- ISO timestamp
    status TEXT DEFAULT 'not_started',
    FOREIGN KEY (question_id) REFERENCES questions(id)
);

CREATE TABLE business_directions (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,
    name TEXT NOT NULL,
    description TEXT,
    selected INTEGER DEFAULT 0,
    created_at TEXT
);
@end example


@subsection Config Schema (Simplified)


@example
@{
  "form_name": "Oregon SEA Application",
  "form_id": "oregon_sea",
  "sections": [
    @{
      "name": "business_overview",
      "title": "Business Overview",
      "questions": [
        @{
          "id": "biz_1",
          "question_text": "What problem does your business solve?",
          "question_type": "long_text",
          "priority": 1,
          "helper_text": "Think about..."
        @}
      ]
    @}
  ]
@}
@end example



@section Invariants

Properties that must always hold:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Every question has a unique ID} within a config
@item
@strong{Answer status is one of:} @code{not_started}, @code{in_progress}, @code{complete}
@item
@strong{Priority is 1, 2, or 3} (1 = highest)
@item
@strong{depends_on references existing question IDs}
@item
@strong{Database and config stay in sync} (questions table mirrors config)
@item
@strong{Claude session files are ephemeral} (deleted or overwritten each session)
@end enumerate



@section Extension Points

Where the architecture anticipates change:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{New question types} - Add to schema, update UI rendering
@item
@strong{New export formats} - Add exporter function, register in CLI
@item
@strong{New storage backends} - Replace @code{sea_application_helper.py} (RFC 001/002)
@item
@strong{New AI integrations} - Replace Claude subprocess with different agent
@item
@strong{Business directions} - Optional feature, can be extended or removed
@end enumerate



@section Known Limitations

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Single-user} - No collaboration features
@item
@strong{Local-only} - No sync, cloud backup
@item
@strong{Sequential Claude sessions} - Can't run multiple in parallel
@item
@strong{No undo} - Answers overwrite, history only in session_log
@item
@strong{English-only} - No i18n support
@item
@strong{No encryption} - Answers stored in plaintext
@end enumerate



