@node RFC 002
@chapter RFC 002: Memory Layer Specification


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Implemented (v0.3.0, extended in v0.5.0)

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-02-05

@noindent
@strong{Implemented:} 2026-02-05 (tasks, decisions); 2026-02-20 (facts — RFC 004)

@noindent
@strong{Parent:} RFC 001


@quotation
@strong{Note:} The default prefix changed from @code{fc} to @code{sm} in RFC 004.
@end quotation
@quotation
The semantic (facts) store was added in RFC 004 as a third typed
@end quotation
@quotation
memory store alongside tasks and decisions.
@end quotation


@section Purpose

Document the essential patterns from @uref{https://github.com/steveyegge/beads, beads} and @uref{https://github.com/m0n0x41d/quint-code, quint-code} for pure Python implementation. This spec captures what we need, not everything those tools offer.



@section Part 1: Task Graph (inspired by beads)


@subsection Core Concepts

@strong{Task}: A unit of work with identity, status, and relationships.

@strong{Identity}: Hash-based IDs avoid merge conflicts in concurrent/multi-session scenarios.
@itemize @bullet
@item
Format: @code{@{prefix@}-@{5-char-alphanum@}} (e.g., @code{fc-a1b2c})
@item
Prefix configurable per project (default: @code{fc} for form-copilot)
@end itemize

@strong{Hierarchy}: Tasks can have parent/child relationships.
@itemize @bullet
@item
Notation: @code{fc-a1b2c.1} is first child of @code{fc-a1b2c}
@item
Enables: epic → task → subtask structures
@end itemize

@strong{Dependencies}: Tasks can block other tasks.
@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{blocks}: List of task IDs that cannot start until this completes
@item
@code{blocked_by}: List of task IDs that must complete before this starts
@end itemize

@strong{Status}: Lifecycle states.
@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{open} → @code{in_progress} → @code{closed}
@item
@code{archived} (for compacted/decayed tasks)
@end itemize


@subsection Data Model


@example
@@dataclass
class Task:
    id: str                      # fc-a1b2c
    title: str                   # Short description
    description: str             # Full content (answers, notes)
    status: str                  # open, in_progress, closed, archived
    parent_id: Optional[str]     # Parent task ID
    blocks: List[str]            # Task IDs this blocks
    blocked_by: List[str]        # Task IDs blocking this
    labels: List[str]            # Freeform tags
    created_at: str              # ISO timestamp
    updated_at: str              # ISO timestamp
    metadata: Dict[str, Any]     # Extensible properties
@end example


@subsection Storage Format

@strong{Primary}: JSONL file (one task per line, append-friendly)

@example
@{"id":"fc-a1b2c","title":"...","status":"open",...@}
@{"id":"fc-d3e4f","title":"...","status":"closed",...@}
@end example

@strong{Location}: @code{.memory/tasks.jsonl}

@strong{Index}: SQLite cache for queries (regenerable from JSONL)

@example
CREATE TABLE tasks (
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    title TEXT,
    status TEXT,
    parent_id TEXT,
    created_at TEXT,
    updated_at TEXT
);
CREATE TABLE task_labels (task_id TEXT, label TEXT);
CREATE TABLE task_blocks (task_id TEXT, blocks_id TEXT);
@end example


@subsection Operations


@multitable @columnfractions 0.50 0.50
@headitem Operation @tab Description
@item @code{create(title, description, parent_id?, labels?)} @tab Create task, generate ID
@item @code{get(id)} @tab Retrieve single task
@item @code{update(id, fields)} @tab Modify task fields
@item @code{close(id)} @tab Mark task closed
@item @code{list(status?, label?, parent_id?)} @tab Query tasks
@item @code{ready()} @tab List tasks with no unresolved blocked_by
@item @code{block(id, blocks_id)} @tab Add dependency
@item @code{unblock(id, blocks_id)} @tab Remove dependency
@item @code{children(id)} @tab List child tasks
@item @code{history(id)} @tab List all versions of task
@end multitable



@subsection ID Generation


@example
import hashlib
import time

def generate_id(prefix: str = "fc") -> str:
    """Generate hash-based task ID."""
    seed = f"@{time.time_ns()@}@{random.random()@}"
    hash_bytes = hashlib.sha256(seed.encode()).digest()
    alphanum = base32_encode(hash_bytes)[:5].lower()
    return f"@{prefix@}-@{alphanum@}"
@end example



@section Part 2: Decision Trails (inspired by quint)


@subsection Core Concepts

@strong{Decision}: A recorded reasoning process for non-trivial choices.

@strong{Hypothesis}: A candidate approach being considered.
@itemize @bullet
@item
Multiple hypotheses generated before selection
@item
Each has rationale and confidence score
@end itemize

@strong{Workflow}: Structured reasoning phases.
@enumerate
@item
@strong{Abduction} - Generate multiple hypotheses (don't anchor on first idea)
@item
@strong{Deduction} - Check logical consistency, constraints
@item
@strong{Induction} - Test against evidence, examples
@item
@strong{Selection} - Choose hypothesis with rationale
@end enumerate

@strong{Audit Trail}: Decisions are queryable later.
@itemize @bullet
@item
"Why did I choose this framing?"
@item
"What alternatives did I consider?"
@end itemize


@subsection Data Model


@example
@@dataclass
class Hypothesis:
    id: str                      # h1, h2, h3
    description: str             # The approach
    rationale: str               # Why it might work
    confidence: float            # 0.0 - 1.0

@@dataclass
class Decision:
    id: str                      # qt-a1b2c
    context: str                 # What we're deciding
    task_id: Optional[str]       # Related task (if any)
    hypotheses: List[Hypothesis] # Options considered
    selected: Optional[str]      # Chosen hypothesis ID
    selection_rationale: str     # Why this choice
    phase: str                   # abduction, deduction, induction, decided
    created_at: str
    decided_at: Optional[str]
@end example


@subsection Storage Format

@strong{Primary}: JSONL file

@example
@{"id":"qt-a1b2c","context":"How to frame leadership answer",...@}
@end example

@strong{Location}: @code{.memory/decisions.jsonl}


@subsection Operations


@multitable @columnfractions 0.50 0.50
@headitem Operation @tab Description
@item @code{begin(context, task_id?)} @tab Start decision, phase=abduction
@item @code{hypothesize(decision_id, description, rationale)} @tab Add hypothesis
@item @code{verify(decision_id)} @tab Move to deduction phase
@item @code{test(decision_id)} @tab Move to induction phase
@item @code{decide(decision_id, hypothesis_id, rationale)} @tab Select and close
@item @code{get(id)} @tab Retrieve decision
@item @code{list(task_id?, phase?)} @tab Query decisions
@item @code{for_task(task_id)} @tab All decisions related to task
@end multitable




@section Part 3: Synthesis


@subsection Core Concepts

@strong{Synthesis}: Analysis that extracts insights from accumulated tasks and decisions.

@strong{Pattern Detection}: Find recurring themes, gaps, inconsistencies.

@strong{Cross-Reference}: Connect related items across different contexts.

@strong{Decay}: Compress old items while preserving essential insights.


@subsection Operations


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Operation @tab Input @tab Output
@item @code{patterns(label?, since?)} @tab Filter criteria @tab List of detected patterns
@item @code{connections(task_id)} @tab Single task @tab Related tasks and decisions
@item @code{decay(older_than)} @tab Age threshold @tab Summary of archived items
@end multitable



@subsection Synthesis Output Model


@example
@@dataclass
class Pattern:
    description: str             # What was detected
    evidence: List[str]          # Task/decision IDs supporting this
    confidence: float            # How strong the pattern is

@@dataclass
class Connection:
    source_id: str               # Starting point
    target_id: str               # Connected item
    relationship: str            # How they connect
    strength: float              # Connection strength

@@dataclass
class DecaySummary:
    archived_count: int          # Items compressed
    insights: List[str]          # Preserved learnings
    task_ids: List[str]          # What was archived
@end example


@subsection Synthesis Implementation

Synthesis requires LLM reasoning. Implementation:
@enumerate
@item
Load relevant tasks/decisions based on query
@item
Format as prompt context
@item
Call Claude API (or Claude Code subprocess)
@item
Parse structured response
@item
Store synthesis results as special task (label: @code{synthesis})
@end enumerate



@section Part 4: Storage Layout


@example
.memory/
├── tasks.jsonl          # All tasks (append-only log)
├── decisions.jsonl      # All decisions (append-only log)
├── index.db             # SQLite cache (regenerable)
├── config.json          # Prefix, settings
└── archive/
    └── 2026-01/         # Monthly archives after decay
        ├── tasks.jsonl
        └── synthesis.md
@end example


@subsection Config


@example
@{
  "prefix": "fc",
  "version": "1.0",
  "created_at": "2026-02-05T00:00:00Z"
@}
@end example



@section Part 5: CLI Interface


@subsection Task Commands


@example
# Create
memory task create "Answer business overview question" --label question --label priority:1

# List
memory task list                    # All open
memory task list --status closed    # Closed only
memory task ready                   # Unblocked tasks

# Update
memory task close fc-a1b2c
memory task block fc-a1b2c fc-d3e4f  # a1b2c blocks d3e4f

# View
memory task show fc-a1b2c
memory task history fc-a1b2c
@end example


@subsection Decision Commands


@example
# Start decision
memory decide begin "How to frame technical background" --task fc-a1b2c

# Add hypotheses
memory decide hypo qt-x1y2z "Lead with Intel experience" --confidence 0.7
memory decide hypo qt-x1y2z "Lead with recent AI work" --confidence 0.8

# Complete
memory decide select qt-x1y2z h2 --rationale "AI work is more relevant to this role"

# Query
memory decide show qt-x1y2z
memory decide for-task fc-a1b2c
@end example


@subsection Synthesis Commands


@example
# Analyze
memory synthesize patterns --label question
memory synthesize connections fc-a1b2c
memory synthesize decay --older-than 30d
@end example



@section Part 6: Python API


@example
from memory import Memory

# Initialize
mem = Memory(".memory")

# Tasks
task = mem.tasks.create("Answer question", description="...", labels=["question"])
mem.tasks.update(task.id, status="in_progress")
ready = mem.tasks.ready()
mem.tasks.close(task.id)

# Decisions
decision = mem.decisions.begin("How to frame answer", task_id=task.id)
mem.decisions.hypothesize(decision.id, "Option A", rationale="...")
mem.decisions.hypothesize(decision.id, "Option B", rationale="...")
mem.decisions.decide(decision.id, "h1", rationale="Better fit")

# Synthesis
patterns = mem.synthesize.patterns(label="question")
connections = mem.synthesize.connections(task.id)
@end example



@section Implementation Notes


@subsection Why JSONL + SQLite?

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{JSONL}: Append-only, git-friendly, human-readable, no corruption on crash
@item
@strong{SQLite}: Fast queries, indexes, but regenerable from JSONL source of truth
@end itemize


@subsection Why Hash IDs?

@itemize @bullet
@item
No coordination needed between sessions
@item
No merge conflicts
@item
Short enough to type/reference
@end itemize


@subsection Git Integration

@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{.memory/} is tracked in git
@item
JSONL files merge cleanly (append-only)
@item
@code{index.db} in @code{.gitignore} (regenerable)
@end itemize



@section Future Considerations


@subsection SQLite as Memory Backend

The Memory API could support pluggable storage backends:


@example
# Current: JSONL + SQLite index
memory = Memory(".memory", backend="jsonl")

# Future: Pure SQLite backend
memory = Memory(".memory", backend="sqlite")

# Future: Remote/cloud backend
memory = Memory(".memory", backend="s3")
@end example

SQLite as a backend would:
@itemize @bullet
@item
Keep the Memory API as the interface
@item
Store tasks/decisions in SQLite tables directly
@item
Remove JSONL layer for simpler stack
@item
Trade git-friendliness for query performance
@end itemize

This is a future refactor option if JSONL complexity becomes burdensome.



