@node RFC 003
@chapter RFC 003: Recursive Context and Complementary Cognition


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Partially Implemented (v0.4.0)

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson + Claude

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-02-05

@noindent
@strong{Implemented:} 2026-02-17 (P1, P3); P2, P4 deferred

@noindent
@strong{References:} Zhang, Kraska, Khattab. "Recursive Language Models." arXiv:2512.24601v2, Jan 2026.

@noindent
@strong{Parent:} RFC 002 (Memory Layer Spec)



@section Implementation Status


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Proposal @tab Status @tab Notes
@item P1: Dependency graph @tab Implemented (PR #4) @tab @code{blocks}/@code{blocked_by} wired from config @code{depends_on}
@item P2: Contribution tagging @tab Not implemented @tab Deferred — build when session instrumentation is needed
@item P3: Coherence checks @tab Implemented (PR #4) @tab Section-scoped checks, finding categories, @code{CoherenceReport} model
@item P4: Session dimensions @tab Not implemented @tab Deferred — momentum/reach/complementarity metrics not yet needed
@end multitable





@section Summary

This RFC asks whether the Recursive Language Models (RLM) paper offers
anything genuinely useful to form-copilot, or whether it's an interesting
paper about a different problem. The honest answer: **some of it fits
perfectly, some of it is a stretch, and the most interesting part isn't
in the paper at all** --- it's the question of what exactly happens
between two minds when they sit down to answer hard questions together.

We propose three things:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Activate the dependency graph} that already exists in the memory layer
@item
@strong{Instrument complementary cognition} --- not machine metrics, but a
   record of which mind contributed what
@item
**Recognize that the interactive menu's sub-sessions are already
   sub-LM calls** --- RLM gives us vocabulary for what we built
@end enumerate

*The ideas in this RFC are inspired by the RLM paper. Where we draw
on their concepts --- dependency graphs, recursive decomposition,
periodic synthesis --- we cite the source.*



@section Motivation: What the Paper Actually Says

RLM (Zhang et al., 2026) addresses @strong{context rot} --- the degradation
that occurs when you stuff too much text into a language model's context
window. Their solution: don't. Instead, store context as a variable in a
REPL environment and let the model programmatically interact with it,
recursively decomposing problems into sub-problems.

Key claims:

@itemize @bullet
@item
RAG breaks down on multi-hop reasoning (retrieving document A is
  useless unless you already understand document B)
@item
Treating work as a dependency graph enables parallel solving and
  explicit information flow
@item
A small model with RLM scaffolding outperforms a large model running
  blind (RLM + GPT-5-mini beats vanilla GPT-5 by 34%)
@item
Scaffolding alone is insufficient --- learned optimization is essential
@end itemize

The paper's mental model shift: **documents are dependency graphs, not
storybooks.** Don't read start-to-finish. Map the structure, identify
what depends on what, solve leaves first, synthesize upward.



@section What Already Fits (We Built This Without Knowing)

The memory layer (RFC 002) is already an RLM-style environment:


@example
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  RLM Concept              Form Copilot Analog    │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Context as variable  →   tasks.jsonl            │
│  REPL sandbox         →   Claude Code session    │
│  Sub-LM results       →   Context notes          │
│  Recursive calls      →   Queen's garden loop    │
│  Dependency DAG        →   blocks/blocked_by      │
│                            (fields exist, unused) │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
@end example

The queen's garden session that completed 49/49 questions @emph{was} an RLM
in practice. The model never held all 49 answers in its context window.
It held the current question, retrieved relevant context notes from the
JSONL, composed an answer, banked new context, and moved on. Context
lived outside the window as a programmatic object.

The difference: we did this by hand. RLM proposes the model should
decide its own decomposition strategy. For form-copilot, the @emph{human}
decides. That's not a limitation --- it's the point.


@subsection Parallel Evolution

Form-copilot v0.1.0 shipped January 27, 2026. The RLM paper hit arXiv
late December 2025 (v2: January 28, 2026). Neither knew about the
other. Same pressure (context limits degrade quality over long
sessions), same solution (structured resets with persistent external
memory), different domains.

The Python interactive menu --- launching a fresh Claude session per
question with scoped context, getting an answer, piping it back ---
was built to add structure at natural points where the context window
could be reset. That IS the RLM architecture: root process, scoped
recursive calls, results returned to parent. The vocabulary came
later; the instinct came first.


@subsection Hard Wipe vs. Compaction: An Open Question

The queen's garden (one continuous session, 49 questions) hit context
compaction. The system compressed earlier messages to make room. By
question 40-something, details from question 6 were no longer in
active memory --- they had to be retrieved from the JSONL.

The wood approach (fresh session per question) would give each answer
a clean context window with only:

@itemize @bullet
@item
The question and its helper text
@item
Answered dependencies (from memory layer)
@item
Relevant context notes (from memory layer)
@item
Nothing else
@end itemize

No compaction needed. No context rot. The RLM paper's core claim is
that small focused windows with structured retrieval beat one giant
window with everything in it.

@strong{Trade-off:} The queen's garden produces more @emph{connected} answers
(creative leaps between questions, lateral associations). The wood
produces more @emph{consistent} answers (no rot, no compaction artifacts).
A hybrid --- queen's garden in bursts of 5-8 related questions, hard
reset between bursts, coherence check at each boundary --- may be
the best of both.

This is testable. Same questions, both approaches, compare coherence
and contradiction rates. Future work.



@section What Doesn't Fit (And Why That's Fine)


@subsection Recursive sub-LM calls

RLM spawns isolated child language model instances to process subsets
of data. Form-copilot's interactive menu @emph{already does this} --- press
@code{[C]} on a question and it launches a Claude Code sub-session with
scoped context, gets an answer, and pipes it back to the parent menu.
That IS the RLM pattern: root process → scoped sub-call → result
returned to parent.

The queen's garden collapses this into a single session (no sub-calls,
one continuous conversation). The wood preserves the recursive
structure. Both are valid --- they serve different modes of thinking.

@noindent
@strong{Decision:} Recognize the interactive menu as an existing sub-LM

architecture (inspired by what RLM formalizes). Don't add sub-calls
to the queen's garden --- its value is continuity of conversation.


@subsection Automatic decomposition

RLM lets the model decide how to break down the problem. But the user
already knows their form. They know that the financial section is
stressful and should come after they've built momentum on the business
overview. They know that Q4 (goals) and Q5 (vision) should be
consecutive because the thinking flows. Overriding this with automatic
decomposition would remove the human's agency, which is the opposite
of what we're doing.

@noindent
@strong{Decision:} The human chooses the order. The system can @emph{suggest} an

order based on dependencies, but never impose one.


@subsection Benchmark-style accuracy metrics

The paper measures accuracy on OOLONG and BrowseComp-Plus benchmarks.
Form-copilot has no ground truth --- there is no "correct" answer to
"What is the nature of your business?"

But the absence of accuracy does not mean the absence of measurable
progress. There is @strong{completion} (how many questions answered, how
many dependencies resolved). There is @strong{awareness} (does the user
understand their own situation better after answering Q15 than
before?). There is @strong{progress} (are later answers more specific,
more grounded, more connected to earlier ones than the first few?).

These aren't benchmarks. They're closer to what therapy measures:
not whether the patient gave the "right" answer, but whether the
process moved them forward.

@noindent
@strong{Decision:} Don't measure correctness. Measure completion,

awareness, and coherence as dimensions of progress.



@section What's Genuinely Interesting: Complementary Cognition

The question that matters isn't "can we make the machine faster?" It's
"what is each mind actually doing in this collaboration?"

During the queen's garden session, a pattern emerged that has nothing
to do with RLM and everything to do with how two different kinds of
thinking complement each other:


@subsection What the human brings

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Domain knowledge}: The correct company name, not the model's
  approximation. The actual job title, the real department. The
  specific, lived details that make an answer authentic vs. generic.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Judgment calls}: "Don't list that as a strength --- I've
  struggled with it." The values and self-knowledge that determine
  what's honest vs. what merely sounds good.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Creative leaps}: Lateral connections between industries, people,
  and experiences that a model wouldn't make because they come from
  a life lived, not a corpus searched.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Emotional truth}: The material that transforms a form answer
  from competent to compelling. No model generates this.
@end itemize


@subsection What the model brings

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Holding the thread}: When dozens of questions span financial
  details, competitive analysis, marketing budgets, and personal
  history, the human mind can't hold all of it simultaneously. The
  model can --- not in its context window (that's the whole point
  of the memory layer) but through systematic retrieval: "You
  mentioned this person in Q22 --- should we reference that
  relationship in Q31?"
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Structural coherence}: Making sure the expenses question and
  the cash flow question don't contradict each other. Noticing that
  a budget in one section is too low relative to the targets in
  another. Cross-referencing that's tedious for a human but trivial
  for a machine with structured data.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Articulation}: The human speaks in fragments and associations.
  The model hears the scattered pieces and drafts a coherent
  paragraph that the human can then correct, refine, or reject.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Patient retrieval}: "What did I say about insurance four
  questions ago?" The model doesn't forget, doesn't get bored,
  doesn't lose the thread when attention wanders. This is not
  intelligence --- it's a complementary capability. A prosthetic
  for working memory.
@end itemize


@subsection Neurodivergent-Friendly by Design

Form-copilot works well for minds that operate in bursts, make
lateral leaps, and lose the thread of what they said three questions
ago. The traditional approach --- sit down, read all questions,
answer them linearly, maintain consistency --- assumes a kind of
sustained sequential attention that not everyone has.

The queen's garden workflow works because:

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{No forced order.} Work on what interests you. The memory layer
  catches the dependencies you skip over.
@item
@strong{Context notes as external working memory.} You have a thought
  about Q31 while answering Q6? Bank it. It'll be there when you
  get to Q31.
@item
@strong{The model as a gentle checkpoint.} "You mentioned a budget
  increase --- should the expenses question reflect that?" The model
  being @emph{consistent} complements a mind that's better at divergent
  than convergent thinking.
@end itemize

The wood where things have no names works because:

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Solo pace.} No conversation partner means no social energy drain.
  Just you and the questions, at whatever speed feels right.
@item
@strong{Structure without surveillance.} The menu tracks progress without
  judgment. Come back after a week. It remembers where you were.
@end itemize

This isn't in the RLM paper. But it's the actual value proposition
of form-copilot, and any metrics we collect should measure whether
this complementary relationship is working.


@subsection Interbeing, Not Autonomy

There is a concept in Zen Buddhism --- @emph{non-duality} (@emph{advaita} in
Sanskrit, @emph{not-two}). Thich Nhat Hanh coined the word @strong{interbeing}:
the flower contains the rain, the soil, the sun. Not metaphorically.
Actually. The parts are not separate from the whole.

Applied here: a collaboratively-written answer isn't "the human's" or
"the model's." It's what emerged from the collaboration. The human
brought the concept and the corrections. The model brought structure
and cross-references. The answer is neither mind alone.

So much of the conversation around generative AI is framed as autonomy
and replacement --- will AI take jobs, will it think for itself, should
we fear it. Form-copilot proposes a different frame: **two kinds of
thinking, not separate, producing something neither could alone.** A
thinking journal that two minds wrote together, stored in a format
that outlives both the session and the model.

The memory layer makes this durable. Not just the answers, but (with
the additions proposed here) the record of @emph{how the thinking happened}
--- who contributed what, where coherence emerged, where it broke down.
A journal of interbeing.


@subsection Beyond Forms: The Socratic Extension

A config doesn't have to come from a government application. The
dependency graph and recursive structure could serve open-ended
questions: "What should I do with my life?" "What does my business
actually solve?"

The system could generate sub-questions (Socratic method, therapeutic
framing, structured reflection) and arrange them as a dependency
graph. Answer the leaves, synthesize upward. This is RLM's recursive
decomposition applied not to documents but to @emph{self-knowledge}.

This is noted here as a direction, not a proposal. It would require
a different kind of config --- one generated collaboratively rather
than extracted from a form. But the architecture supports it today.



@section Proposal: What to Actually Build


@subsection P1: Activate the Dependency Graph

The memory layer has @code{blocks} and @code{blocked_by} fields on every task.
They are empty across all 63 tasks in the current dataset. This is
the single most valuable idea from the RLM paper: **make the structure
explicit.**


@example
Q1 (business nature)
├── Q4 (6-12 month goals)
│   └── Q5 (2-3 year vision)
├── Q6 (qualifications)
│   └── Q29 (competitive advantage)
├── Q22a (target market)
│   ├── Q22b (customer acquisition)
│   └── Q23a (pricing)
└── Q15 (income sources)
    ├── Q16 (monthly expenses)
    └── Q17 (cash flow)
@end example

@noindent
@strong{Implementation:} When loading a config, optionally include a

@code{depends_on} field per question. The queen's garden workflow can
use this to suggest order ("Q4 depends on Q1 --- want to do Q1
first?") without enforcing it. The wood can display a readiness
indicator: @code{[R]} for ready (all dependencies answered), @code{[B]} for
blocked (upstream answers missing).

@noindent
@strong{Not proposed:} Automatic dependency inference. The human or the

config author defines dependencies. The system respects them.


@subsection P2: Contribution Tagging

Record, per answer, what each participant contributed. Not as a
score --- as a log.


@example
@{
  "id": "fc-abc12",
  "title": "Q:4 - Short-term goals",
  "metadata": @{
    "contributions": @{
      "human": [
        "core business concept",
        "key partnership identified",
        "revenue framing preference",
        "factual correction on company name"
      ],
      "model": [
        "structured answer from scattered input",
        "cross-referenced startup costs question",
        "surfaced context note from Q1",
        "flagged budget inconsistency"
      ]
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

@noindent
@strong{Why:} This is the data that answers "how does my mind work?" Over

a full application, you can see: when does the human provide raw
material vs. editorial judgment? When does the model retrieve vs.
synthesize? Are there sections where the human does almost everything
(emotional questions, risks) vs. sections where the model does the
heavy lifting (financial consistency, cross-references)?

@noindent
@strong{Collection:} At save time, the model logs a brief contribution

summary. No extra prompting needed --- the model already knows what
it did and what the human provided, because it just had the
conversation.


@subsection P3: Coherence Checks (Inspired by RLM Periodic Synthesis)

A @strong{section boundary pause}: after completing the last question in a
section (e.g., finishing Q19 closes "Financial Due Diligence"), the
system runs a coherence check before moving on. Not after every N
answers --- after each @emph{section}, which is the natural unit of
completeness.

What it looks like in practice:


@example
── Section complete: Financial Due Diligence (5/5) ──

Coherence check:

  ● Monthly expenses question says $X. Cash flow question assumes
    $Y. These reference different time periods. Intentional?

  ● Income sources mention a recurring cost not reflected in
    startup costs. Should it be added?

  ● Strong thread: three answers in this section reference the
    same life transition. This could anchor the financial narrative.

  Continue to next section? [Y/n/fix]
@end example

The check is @strong{blocking} --- it pauses the flow and asks the human
to acknowledge or act. This is metacognition: the process reflecting
on itself in motion. The human can:

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Continue} (the inconsistency is intentional or minor)
@item
@strong{Fix} (go back and revise an answer)
@item
@strong{Note} (bank a context note for later sections)
@end itemize

The coherence check results are saved to the memory layer as a
@code{coherence-check} task type, making them durable. Come back in a
year, and you can see not just the answers but the moments where
the process paused and noticed something.

Implementation: use the synthesis module's @code{patterns()} and
@code{connections()} functions, scoped to the just-completed section
plus any cross-section dependencies.


@subsection P4: Session Dimensions (Three Metrics, Not Thirty)

If we must have numbers, keep it to three that actually mean something:

@strong{Dimension 1: Momentum}
@itemize @bullet
@item
@emph{What it measures:} Is the session flowing or stalling?
@item
@emph{Signal:} Time between answer saves, excluding idle periods
@item
@emph{Unit:} Minutes per answer (rolling average)
@item
@emph{Useful because:} A sudden increase means something is blocking ---
  a hard question, a contradiction, confusion about what's being asked.
  The system could notice and offer help.
@end itemize

@strong{Dimension 2: Reach}
@itemize @bullet
@item
@emph{What it measures:} How connected is the answer graph?
@item
@emph{Signal:} Context notes created, cross-references made, dependency
  edges traversed
@item
@emph{Unit:} Edges per node (graph density)
@item
@emph{Useful because:} A high-reach session produces a coherent narrative.
  A low-reach session produces 49 independent answers that don't talk
  to each other. This is the thing that distinguishes form-copilot
  from "paste each question into ChatGPT separately."
@end itemize

@strong{Dimension 3: Complementarity}
@itemize @bullet
@item
@emph{What it measures:} Are both minds contributing, or is one carrying?
@item
@emph{Signal:} Contribution tags from P2, aggregated per section
@item
@emph{Unit:} Ratio of human-originated to model-originated elements
@item
@emph{Useful because:} If the model is doing everything, the answers
  will be generic. If the human is doing everything, the memory layer
  isn't earning its keep. The sweet spot is balanced contribution
  where each mind does what it's good at.
@end itemize



@section What This Is Not

This is not an agent framework. Form-copilot does not autonomously
complete forms. It does not optimize for speed. It does not replace
human judgment with machine inference.

The RLM paper solves the problem of making machines handle more
context. Form-copilot solves the problem of making humans handle
hard questions. The memory layer is the bridge: it gives the machine
persistence and gives the human a safety net.

Adopting RLM wholesale would mean treating the form as a computation
to be optimized. That misses the point. The 49-question session
worked because a person sat with hard questions, said honest things,
got gentle pushback, revised their thinking, and produced something
that sounds like them. The model helped. The memory layer helped.
But the value was in the thinking, not the throughput.



@section Success Criteria

This proposal succeeds if:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Dependency graph is useful in practice.} When a new user loads
   a config with dependencies, the suggested order feels natural, not
   arbitrary. The @code{[B]}/@code{[R]} indicators in the wood help rather than
   annoy.
@end enumerate

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Contribution logs reveal something interesting.} After a full
   session, reading the contribution summary teaches the user something
   about their own thinking patterns they didn't already know.
@end enumerate

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Coherence checks catch real problems.} At least one contradiction
   or orphaned reference is caught during a session that the user would
   not have noticed on their own.
@end enumerate

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Three metrics, not thirty.} We resist the urge to instrument
   everything. Momentum, reach, and complementarity tell the story.
   If they don't, we have the wrong three --- not too few.
@end enumerate



@section Alternatives Considered


@subsection A1: Full RLM adoption (recursive sub-calls, automatic decomposition)

Rejected. Form-copilot is a conversation tool, not a computation
engine. Spawning sub-LM instances to process form sections in parallel
is technically cool and spiritually wrong. The user wants a thought
partner, not a distributed system.


@subsection A2: No RLM adoption (paper is interesting but irrelevant)

Rejected, but only barely. Most of the paper @emph{is} irrelevant to our
use case. But the dependency graph activation and periodic synthesis
are genuine improvements that we should have built already. The paper
gave us the vocabulary and the inspiration.


@subsection A3: Pure machine metrics (tokens/answer, questions/hour, API cost)

Rejected. These measure the machine's efficiency, not the
collaboration's quality. A session that takes 4 hours and produces
deeply honest answers is better than one that takes 1 hour and
produces generic ones. Optimizing for throughput would optimize for
the wrong thing.


@subsection A4: Full cognitive profiling (detailed executive function metrics)

Rejected on privacy and scope grounds. Recording "time spent
unfocused" or "attention shifts per question" crosses from useful
self-knowledge into surveillance. Contribution tagging is the right
level of granularity: what each mind @emph{did}, not how each mind
@emph{behaved}.



@section Trade-offs Accepted

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Dependency graphs add upfront work.} Someone has to define
  question dependencies in the config. For a large application (40+
  questions), this is maybe 30 minutes of thought. For a quick 10-
  question form, it's probably not worth it. We make it optional.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Contribution tagging is subjective.} The model's summary of "what
  it contributed" is its own assessment, not ground truth. This is
  acceptable because the purpose is reflection, not measurement.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Three metrics means missing things.} Momentum, reach, and
  complementarity don't capture everything. They don't capture answer
  quality, emotional difficulty, or the user's satisfaction. That's
  intentional --- those things resist quantification, and pretending
  otherwise would produce misleading numbers.
@end itemize



@section Implementation Path


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Phase @tab Work @tab Touches
@item 1 @tab Add optional @code{depends_on} to config schema @tab @code{validate_config.py}, @code{CONFIG.md}
@item 2 @tab Wire @code{depends_on} → @code{blocks}/@code{blocked_by} at task creation @tab @code{memory/tasks.py}
@item 3 @tab Add @code{[R]}/@code{[B]} readiness indicators to interactive menu @tab @code{form_copilot.py}
@item 4 @tab Add @code{contributions} field to task metadata at save time @tab queen's garden workflow
@item 5 @tab Add periodic coherence check (every 5 answers) @tab @code{memory/synthesis.py}
@item 6 @tab Add @code{metrics.jsonl} for momentum/reach/complementarity @tab @code{memory/} module
@item 7 @tab Update example configs with question dependencies @tab @code{examples/}
@end multitable




@section References

@itemize @bullet
@item
Zhang, Kraska, Khattab. "Recursive Language Models." arXiv:2512.24601v2. Jan 2026.
@item
RFC 000: Form Copilot Baseline Specification
@item
RFC 002: Memory Layer Specification
@item
Prime Intellect. "Recursive Language Models: The Paradigm of 2026."
@item
Carroll, Lewis. @emph{Through the Looking-Glass}. Chapter III: "Looking-Glass Insects" (the wood where things have no names).
@end itemize


*"Would you tell me, please, which way I ought to go from here?"
"That depends a good deal on where you want to get to," said the Cat.*

*This RFC says: we know where we want to get to. It's not faster
throughput or deeper recursion. It's a better understanding of what
happens when two very different kinds of minds sit down with hard
questions and try to answer them honestly.*



@node RFC 004
@chapter RFC 004: smrti — Rename and Typed Memory


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Implemented (v0.5.0)

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-02-19

@noindent
@strong{Implemented:} 2026-02-20

@noindent
@strong{Parent:} RFC 002



@section Purpose

Rename form-copilot to @strong{smrti} (स्मृति, Sanskrit: "memory,
remembered tradition") and restructure the memory layer around
four typed stores: episodic, semantic, procedural, and
ephemeral. The
repository becomes @strong{advaita-smrti} (अद्वैत-स्मृति, "non-dual
memory").

This RFC covers:
@enumerate
@item
The rename (files, imports, CLI, branch, docs)
@item
Adding semantic (facts) and ephemeral (working) stores
@item
Adopting a typed memory taxonomy from ENGRAM and the
   Google survey paper
@item
What we keep, what we drop, what changes
@end enumerate



@section Motivation


@subsection Why rename

"Form copilot" describes the original scope — helping fill out
multi-section applications. The tool has grown beyond that into
a general memory layer for structured knowledge elicitation.
The name should reflect what it is, not what it started as.

@strong{smrti} means "that which is remembered" — the body of
remembered tradition in Hindu philosophy, as distinct from
shruti ("that which is heard," revealed knowledge). The tool
captures what the human remembers and knows, structures it,
and makes it retrievable. The name fits.

@strong{advaita} means "non-dual." The tool and the thinker are not
separate. The repository name advaita-smrti carries the
philosophy; the CLI and package name smrti stays short for
daily use.


@subsection Why typed memory

The ENGRAM paper (Patel & Patel, 2026) demonstrates that
separating memory into typed stores — episodic, semantic,
procedural — and retrieving from each independently before
merging outperforms systems that dump everything into one
store. Typed separation reduces competition at retrieval time.

Our current memory layer has two stores:
@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{tasks.jsonl} — procedural (questions, dependencies, status)
@item
@code{decisions.jsonl} — episodic (what happened, choices made)
@end itemize

The missing type is @strong{semantic} — stable facts, preferences,
and constraints extracted from conversations and site visits.
Today these live scattered across task descriptions, CLAUDE.md,
or the human's own notes. A dedicated facts store surfaces
them at retrieval time without competing against procedural or
episodic items.


@subsection What makes this different

Every system in the memory literature — ENGRAM, Mem0, Zep,
Letta, MemOS — starts from @strong{conversation} as input. We
start from @strong{structured forms}: sections, questions,
dependencies, priorities. This gives us properties they lack:

@itemize @bullet
@item
The form itself is the procedural memory (no extraction needed)
@item
Coherence checking across answers is built in
@item
Dependency ordering constrains the retrieval problem
@item
There is a clear "done" criterion
@end itemize

This maps to clinical intake, grant applications, legal
discovery, insurance claims — anywhere humans complete complex
multi-part forms with an AI collaborator.



@section Part 1: The Rename


@subsection Files


@multitable @columnfractions 0.50 0.50
@headitem Before @tab After
@item @code{form_copilot.py} @tab @code{smrti.py}
@item repo: @code{form-copilot} @tab repo: @code{advaita-smrti}
@item branch: @code{queens-garden} @tab branch: @code{sutra}
@item prefix: @code{fc} @tab prefix: @code{sm}
@end multitable



@subsection Imports


@example
# Before
from memory import Memory

# After (unchanged — the memory/ package name stays)
from memory import Memory
@end example

The @code{memory/} package is internal and does not need renaming.
External-facing changes are the CLI entry point and repo name.


@subsection CLI


@example
# Before
python3 form_copilot.py memory rebuild
python3 form_copilot.py status

# After
python3 smrti.py memory rebuild
python3 smrti.py status
@end example


@subsection Default branch

The @code{queens-garden} branch name comes from the Alice in
Wonderland theme. Renamed to @strong{sutra} (सूत्र, "thread") —
continues the Sanskrit theme, evokes the thread of
continuity running through the memory stores.


@subsection What stays

@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{memory/} package directory and all its modules
@item
@code{sea_application_helper.py} (the SEA form helper)
@item
@code{sea_assistant.py} (interactive assistant)
@item
@code{examples/}, @code{tests/}, @code{docs/}
@item
JSONL + SQLite storage architecture
@item
All existing tests (updated imports only)
@end itemize


@subsection What gets removed or renamed

@itemize @bullet
@item
All string references to "form-copilot" and "form_copilot"
@item
The Alice in Wonderland release names in CHANGELOG.md
@end itemize



@section Part 2: Typed Memory Stores


@subsection Taxonomy

Combines ENGRAM's typed stores (Patel & Patel, 2026) with the
working memory concept from the Google survey (Hu et al., 2025).


@multitable @columnfractions 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25
@headitem Type @tab What it stores @tab Persisted @tab Current analog
@item @strong{Procedural} @tab Tasks, workflows, deps @tab yes, @code{tasks.jsonl} @tab existing
@item @strong{Episodic} @tab Events, decisions, cases @tab yes, @code{decisions.jsonl} @tab existing
@item @strong{Semantic} @tab Stable facts, preferences @tab yes, @code{facts.jsonl} @tab @emph{missing}
@item @strong{Ephemeral} @tab Active session workspace @tab no, @code{ephemeral/} @tab implicit (context files)
@end multitable



@subsection New: Semantic Store (@code{facts.jsonl})

A new JSONL file and corresponding SQLite index table for
extracted facts.


@example
@@dataclass
class Fact:
    id: str              # sm-f-xxxxx
    fact: str            # "Business registered in Oregon"
    source: str          # "application_q3"
    section: str         # Optional section grouping
    confidence: float    # 0.0-1.0
    labels: List[str]    # Freeform tags
    supersedes: str      # ID of fact this replaces (if updated)
    created_at: str      # ISO timestamp
    updated_at: str      # ISO timestamp
    metadata: dict       # Extensible
@end example


@subsubsection API


@example
mem = Memory(".memory")

# Create
fact = mem.facts.create(
    "Business registered in Oregon",
    source="application_q3",
    section="legal",
)

# Update (creates new version, marks old as superseded)
mem.facts.update(fact.id, fact="Business registered in Oregon since 2024")

# Query
facts = mem.facts.by_section("legal")
facts = mem.facts.by_label("requirement")
facts = mem.facts.search("oregon")  # substring match

# All
all_facts = mem.facts.all()
@end example


@subsubsection SQLite index additions


@example
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS facts (
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    fact TEXT,
    source TEXT,
    section TEXT,
    confidence REAL,
    supersedes TEXT,
    created_at TEXT,
    updated_at TEXT
);

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS fact_labels (
    fact_id TEXT,
    label TEXT,
    PRIMARY KEY (fact_id, label)
);

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_facts_section ON facts(section);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_facts_source ON facts(source);
@end example


@subsubsection Drift detection

The existing drift detection extends to cover facts:


@example
Tasks:     JSONL has N, index has M
Decisions: JSONL has N, index has M
Facts:     JSONL has N, index has M
@end example


@subsection New: Ephemeral Store (@code{ephemeral/})

The ephemeral store holds transient state for the active
session. It is not appended to JSONL — it lives in a
directory that is cleared or rolled into episodic memory
when the session ends.


@subsubsection What goes here

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Active question context} — the current question being
  worked on, related answers pulled from other stores, notes
  in progress. Currently @code{.sea_question_context.json}.
@item
@strong{Draft state} — the answer being composed. Currently
  @code{.sea_answer.md}.
@item
@strong{Session scratch} — what's been discussed this session,
  intermediate reasoning, temporary notes.
@item
@strong{Retrieved context} — facts, tasks, and decisions pulled
  from the persistent stores for the current task.
@end itemize


@subsubsection Lifecycle


@example
session start  → ephemeral/ created (or cleared)
during session → files written and read freely
session end    → option to:
                   (a) discard (default)
                   (b) promote to episodic (save as decision)
                   (c) extract facts to semantic store
@end example


@subsubsection Structure


@example
ephemeral/
  context.json      # Current question/task context
  draft.md          # Answer or artifact in progress
  retrieved/        # Cached retrievals from other stores
    facts.json      # Relevant facts for current task
    tasks.json      # Related tasks
    decisions.json  # Related prior decisions
@end example


@subsubsection Why "ephemeral" not "working"

The Google survey calls this "working memory." We call it
@strong{ephemeral} to emphasize that it is not persisted by
default. The cognitive science term "working memory" implies
a fixed-capacity buffer; our ephemeral store is simply
session-scoped scratch space with no capacity constraint.
The name also avoids confusion with a directory name
suggesting permanence — it is explicitly temporary.


@subsection Coherence checking additions

The existing @code{coherence_check()} gains a new category:

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{fact_conflict}: Two facts in the same section contradict
  each other (e.g., two different addresses)
@item
@strong{fact_staleness}: A fact's source is older than a threshold
  and may need re-verification
@end itemize


@subsection What we defer

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Vector embeddings / cosine similarity} — our dataset is
  small enough for exact match and substring search. Embeddings
  can be added later without changing the store schema (the
  ENGRAM embedding field is optional).
@item
@strong{LLM-powered router} — ENGRAM uses an LLM call to classify
  each incoming utterance into memory types. For now, routing
  is human-directed (the user or Claude explicitly calls
  @code{facts.create()} vs @code{tasks.create()} vs @code{decisions.begin()}).
  A router can be added as a convenience layer later.
@item
@strong{Cross-type retrieval merging} — ENGRAM merges top-k from
  each store at query time. We don't need this yet because our
  queries are type-specific (show me all facts, show me ready
  tasks). When we add a natural-language query interface, this
  becomes relevant.
@item
@strong{Temporal decay for facts} — facts don't decay the same way
  tasks do. A fact is true until superseded. The @code{supersedes}
  field handles versioning without decay.
@end itemize



@section Part 3: Documentation


@subsection README rewrite

The README becomes succinct and forward-looking:

@enumerate
@item
One paragraph: what smrti is
@item
The four memory types (table)
@item
Quick-start (install, configure, run)
@item
CLI reference
@item
Inspirations and references:
@itemize @bullet
@item
beads — git-backed task graphs (original inspiration)
@item
quint-code — decision reasoning trails (original inspiration)
@item
ENGRAM (arxiv 2511.12960) — typed memory stores
@item
Memory in the Age of AI Agents (arxiv 2512.13564) — survey/taxonomy
@item
Google/Kaggle: Context Engineering: Sessions & Memory
@end itemize
@item
See also: Zep, Letta, Mem0, Pinecone (landscape context)
@end enumerate

Drop: project evolution history, Alice in Wonderland references,
lengthy CHANGELOG prose.


@subsection CLAUDE.md update

Update the memory layer section to reflect four stores and
the @code{smrti.py} entry point.


@subsection CHANGELOG

Start fresh with v0.5.0 or v1.0.0 for the rename. Previous
history preserved in git.



@section References

@itemize @bullet
@item
Patel, D. & Patel, S. (2026). ENGRAM: Effective, Lightweight
  Memory Orchestration for Conversational Agents.
  arXiv:2511.12960.
@item
Hu, Y. et al. (2025). Memory in the Age of AI Agents: A
  Survey. arXiv:2512.13564.
@item
Google. (2025). Context Engineering: Sessions & Memory.
  Kaggle whitepaper.
@item
Yegge, S. beads — git-backed task graphs.
  github.com/steveyegge/beads.
@item
quint-code — decision reasoning trails.
  github.com/m0n0x41d/quint-code.
@end itemize


@section Decisions (resolved during implementation)

