@node RFC 005
@chapter RFC 005: Ephemeral Store


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Draft

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-02-19

@noindent
@strong{Parent:} @strong{RFC 004}



@section Purpose

Define the ephemeral memory store — session-scoped scratch
space that bridges the gap between an AI agent's conversation
context and smrti's durable stores.



@section Problem

When Claude Code works on a smrti project, two memory systems
operate independently:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Anthropic's session context} — task tracking, conversation
   history, tool results. Ephemeral by design: gone when the
   session ends or the context window compresses.
@end enumerate

@enumerate
@item
@strong{smrti's durable stores} — tasks.jsonl (procedural),
   decisions.jsonl (episodic), facts.jsonl (semantic). Persistent,
   git-backed, survive across sessions.
@end enumerate

The gap: valuable session state that isn't yet ready for a durable
store has nowhere to land. Draft answers, working hypotheses,
partial extractions, scratch calculations — these either live only
in the agent's context (lost on session end) or get prematurely
committed to a durable store (polluting it with noise).



@section Proposal


@subsection The ephemeral/ directory


@example
.memory/
├── tasks.jsonl        # procedural (durable)
├── decisions.jsonl    # episodic (durable)
├── facts.jsonl        # semantic (durable)
├── index.db           # regenerable cache
├── config.json
└── ephemeral/         # session scratch (not persisted)
    ├── session.json   # current session metadata
    ├── scratch.md     # freeform working notes
    └── staging/       # items being prepared for durable stores
@end example


@subsection What goes in ephemeral/


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Content @tab Example @tab Destination after triage
@item Draft answers @tab Half-written response to Q3 @tab tasks.jsonl (when finalized)
@item Working hypotheses @tab "Maybe the revenue model is subscription" @tab decisions.jsonl (if worth recording)
@item Extracted candidates @tab Facts noticed but not yet verified @tab facts.jsonl (if confirmed)
@item Session metadata @tab Start time, questions touched, agent ID @tab Discarded or logged
@item Scratch notes @tab Calculations, comparisons, outlines @tab Discarded
@end multitable



@subsection Lifecycle

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Session start} — create @code{ephemeral/session.json} with
   timestamp and session ID
@item
@strong{During session} — agent writes scratch files as needed.
   No schema enforced. Plain text, JSON, markdown — whatever
   the agent finds useful.
@item
@strong{Triage} — before session end, the agent (or human) reviews
   ephemeral/ and promotes anything worth keeping into the
   appropriate durable store via the Python API.
@item
@strong{Session end} — @code{ephemeral/} is cleared. The .gitignore
   already excludes it.
@end enumerate


@subsection Not persisted

The ephemeral directory is:
@itemize @bullet
@item
Listed in @code{.gitignore} (never committed)
@item
Cleared on session start (previous session's scratch is gone)
@item
Not backed by SQLite (no index, no drift detection)
@item
Not included in @code{smrti.py memory rebuild} or @code{compact}
@end itemize

This is intentional. Ephemeral memory is disposable by definition.



@section Overlap with Anthropic session tools

Anthropic's built-in @code{TaskCreate}/@code{TaskUpdate} tools serve a
similar purpose: tracking work items within a single conversation.
They are ephemeral — gone when the session ends.


@subsection Where they differ


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Aspect @tab Anthropic session tools @tab smrti ephemeral/
@item Scope @tab Conversation context @tab File system
@item Survives context compression @tab No @tab Yes (until session end)
@item Structured @tab Yes (task model) @tab No (freeform)
@item Accessible to human @tab Only via agent @tab Directly readable files
@item Promotable to durable store @tab Manual (agent must extract) @tab Direct (files are right there)
@end multitable



@subsection The bridge value

The key insight: Anthropic's tools track @emph{agent work}, while
smrti's ephemeral store holds @emph{domain knowledge in progress}.

A session where the agent answers 5 application questions might
use Anthropic's task tools to track "answer Q1, Q2, Q3..."
while using ephemeral/ to hold:
@itemize @bullet
@item
Draft text for Q3 that the human hasn't reviewed yet
@item
A fact extracted from the Q1 discussion that applies to Q5
@item
A note that Q2 and Q4 have contradictory assumptions
@end itemize

These are different concerns. The agent's work tracker doesn't
need to persist. The domain scratch does — at least until triage.


@subsection Future: automatic triage

A natural extension (not in this RFC): at session end, the
agent could automatically scan ephemeral/ and propose
promotions:


@example
Session ending. Found in ephemeral/:
  - scratch.md: 3 candidate facts identified
  - staging/q3-draft.md: draft answer for Q3

Promote to durable stores?
  [1] Extract facts to facts.jsonl
  [2] Save Q3 draft to tasks.jsonl
  [3] Discard all
  [4] Review individually
@end example

This bridges the two systems without coupling them.



@section Implementation


@subsection Phase 1 (minimal)

@itemize @bullet
@item
Create @code{ephemeral/} directory on Memory init
@item
Add @code{.gitignore} entry for @code{ephemeral/}
@item
Add @code{Memory.ephemeral_path} property
@item
Add @code{Memory.clear_ephemeral()} method
@item
No schema, no models, no SQLite
@end itemize


@subsection Phase 2 (session awareness)

@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{session.json} with start time, session ID
@item
@code{Memory.start_session()} / @code{Memory.end_session()}
@item
Automatic clear on new session start
@end itemize


@subsection Phase 3 (triage helpers)

@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{Memory.promote_fact(path)} — read file, create fact
@item
@code{Memory.promote_draft(path, task_id)} — attach to task
@item
CLI: @code{smrti.py memory triage}
@end itemize



@section Open questions

@enumerate
@item
Should ephemeral/ contents survive across sessions if
   the human explicitly asks? (A "pin" mechanism?)
@item
Should there be a TTL — auto-clear after N hours even
   without a new session?
@item
Is @code{staging/} a useful sub-convention or over-engineering
   for Phase 1?
@end enumerate



@section References

@itemize @bullet
@item
RFC 004: smrti rename and typed memory (parent)
@item
ENGRAM (arxiv:2511.12960) — procedural memory as working buffer
@item
Google Context Engineering whitepaper — session management
@item
Letta — filesystem memory that outperforms specialized systems
@end itemize



@node RFC 006
@chapter RFC 006: Web Interface — Resume Fit and Honest Discovery


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Concept

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-02-20

@noindent
@strong{Parent:} @strong{RFC 004}, @strong{RFC 005}



@section Purpose

Extend smrti beyond Claude Code and Python API to a
public-facing web interface. A visitor pastes a job
description; the system returns an honest assessment of
fit against the host's resume/experience, drawn from
smrti's semantic store.



@section Problem

Today, smrti's knowledge is only accessible through:
@itemize @bullet
@item
Claude Code sessions (developer tooling)
@item
Python API (@code{from memory import Memory})
@end itemize

A recruiter, hiring manager, or company contact who has
received an application has no way to explore the
candidate's fit without scheduling a call. The candidate
has no way to pre-qualify opportunities without reading
every job description manually.

The gap: @strong{no self-service discovery layer} between
"received a resume" and "scheduled a meeting."



@section Proposal


@subsection The visitor experience

@enumerate
@item
Visitor arrives at a personal/professional site
@item
Pastes a job description into a text box (or uploads PDF)
@item
System computes fit against the host's experience
@item
Returns:
@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Fit likelihood} (high / moderate / low / unclear)
@item
@strong{Relevant experience} — tailored list drawn from
     facts store, honest, not fabricated
@item
@strong{Gaps or uncertainties} — areas where the fit is
     unclear, with follow-up questions the visitor could
     ask to clarify
@item
@strong{Work preferences} — full-time vs. contract vs.
     retainer, and what the host is currently open to
@end itemize
@item
If fit is good: @strong{call to action} to schedule an
   appointment to discuss a project or role
@item
If fit is low: honest about it. Sets expectations.
   May suggest adjacent roles or referrals.
@end enumerate


@subsection What it is NOT

@itemize @bullet
@item
Not a chatbot. One input, one structured response.
@item
Not a hallucination engine. Every claim traces to a
  fact in the semantic store with source attribution.
@item
Not a generic AI resume tool. It represents ONE person's
  actual experience, preferences, and constraints.
@end itemize



@section How smrti fits

smrti becomes the @strong{knowledge backend}:


@example
┌─────────────────────────────────┐
│  Web UI (visitor-facing)        │
│  - Paste job description        │
│  - View fit assessment          │
│  - Schedule if good fit         │
└──────────────┬──────────────────┘
               │
┌──────────────▼──────────────────┐
│  Fit Engine                     │
│  - Parse job requirements       │
│  - Query facts by section/label │
│  - Match requirements to facts  │
│  - Score fit, surface gaps      │
│  - Generate honest response     │
└──────────────┬──────────────────┘
               │
┌──────────────▼──────────────────┐
│  smrti semantic store           │
│  facts.jsonl — skills, history, │
│  preferences, constraints       │
│  Curated by host, not generated │
└─────────────────────────────────┘
@end example


@subsection Facts as the source of truth

The fit engine only claims what the facts store contains.
Example facts:


@example
"10 years Python experience" (source: resume, confidence: 1.0)
"Led team of 5 on kiosk project" (source: portfolio, confidence: 1.0)
"Familiar with React, not expert" (source: self-assessment, confidence: 0.7)
"Prefers contract/retainer over full-time" (source: preference, confidence: 0.9)
"Open to full-time for the right fit" (source: preference, confidence: 0.6)
@end example

The response references these facts. The visitor sees
evidence, not claims. Low-confidence facts surface as
"may be relevant, worth discussing" rather than assertions.


@subsection Work preference signaling

The facts store holds explicit preference facts:


@multitable @columnfractions 0.50 0.50
@headitem Preference @tab Signal
@item Contract (project-based) @tab Preferred — strongest fit
@item Retainer @tab Open — good for ongoing needs
@item Full-time @tab Selective — depends on role/culture
@item Remote @tab Required / preferred / flexible
@item Location @tab Constraints if any
@end multitable


These shape the call to action. A recruiter filling a
full-time role sees "open to full-time for the right fit"
with an invitation to discuss. A company with a 3-month
project sees "this is the sweet spot" with a direct
scheduling link.



@section Interfaces


@subsection Option A: Static site + API

@itemize @bullet
@item
Simple HTML/JS frontend (no framework needed)
@item
API endpoint that accepts job description text
@item
LLM call to parse requirements and match against facts
@item
Response rendered as structured HTML
@end itemize


@subsection Option B: MCP server

@itemize @bullet
@item
smrti exposed as an MCP tool
@item
Any MCP-compatible client can query fit
@item
Web UI is one client; Claude Desktop is another
@item
Richer interaction possible (follow-up questions)
@end itemize


@subsection Option C: Both

@itemize @bullet
@item
MCP server as the core interface
@item
Web UI as a thin client over MCP
@item
Claude Code sessions also use MCP for fact queries
@end itemize

Decision deferred to implementation.



@section Tone and honesty

The system's voice should be:
@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Honest} — "I don't have deep experience in X" is
  a valid and valuable response
@item
@strong{Specific} — "I led a 5-person team on a kiosk
  project for a day center" not "experienced team leader"
@item
@strong{Curious} — when fit is unclear, ask the visitor
  what they're actually looking for rather than guessing
@item
@strong{Respectful of the visitor's time} — if fit is low,
  say so early. Don't waste a meeting on a mismatch.
@end itemize

This is the advaita principle in practice: the interface
and the person are not separate. The system speaks as
the host would speak, with the host's actual knowledge
and the host's actual limitations.



@section Prior art and references

@itemize @bullet
@item
Nate B. Jones — ideas on AI-powered professional
  presence and self-service discovery (YouTube, potential
  subscription for deeper dive)
@item
Damian Galarza — context engineering and memory for
  AI agents (YouTube)
@item
Personal CRM / portfolio tools that do static
  presentation but not interactive fit assessment
@end itemize



@section Open questions

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Privacy} — job descriptions pasted by visitors may
   contain confidential information. How do we handle
   data retention? Process and discard? Log for the host?
@item
@strong{Rate limiting} — prevent abuse without requiring
   login
@item
@strong{Fact curation} — who maintains the facts store?
   Host manually? Semi-automated from resume/portfolio?
@item
@strong{LLM dependency} — the fit engine needs an LLM for
   parsing and matching. Which provider? Cost per query?
   Can we do a first-pass with keyword matching and only
   escalate to LLM for ambiguous cases?
@item
@strong{Scheduling integration} — Calendly? Cal.com? Simple
   email link?
@item
@strong{Scope of v1} — is the MVP just the text box and
   fit response, or does it include the scheduling CTA?
@end enumerate



@section Relationship to other RFCs

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{RFC 004} — the semantic (facts) store is the
  knowledge backend for this interface
@item
@strong{RFC 005} — ephemeral store could hold visitor
  session state during a fit assessment
@item
@strong{RFC 003} — complementary cognition: the visitor
  brings the job context, the system brings the
  candidate knowledge. Neither has the full picture alone.
@end itemize



@node RFC 007
@chapter RFC 007: Python Packaging and Repo Layout


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Concept

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-02-20

@noindent
@strong{Parent:} @strong{RFC 004}

@noindent
@strong{Trigger:} When PyPI publishing or RFC 006 (web interface) forces it



@section Purpose

Reorganize the repository into a standard Python package
layout. Consolidate loose top-level files to push the
rendered README above the fold on GitHub. Separate library
code from application code.



@section Problem

The current top level has ~20 visible entries. GitHub
renders the file listing before the README, pushing it
below the fold. More importantly, the layout conflates
three concerns:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Library} (@code{memory/}) — the reusable memory layer
@item
@strong{Application} (@code{sea_application_helper.py},
   @code{sea_assistant.py}) — SEA-grant-specific code
@item
@strong{Tooling} (@code{validate_config.py}, @code{export_docs.py},
   @code{migrate_to_memory.py}) — utility scripts
@end enumerate

These should be separate.



@section Current layout (20 rows)


@example
.claude/
.github/
docs/
examples/
hooks/
memory/
tests/
business_direction_analysis.md
CHANGELOG.md
CLAUDE.md
config_schema.json
export_docs.py
LICENSE
migrate_to_memory.py
README.md
sea_application_helper.py
sea_assistant.py
smrti.py
validate_config.py
.gitignore
@end example


@section Proposed layout (6 rows)


@example
advaita-smrti/
├── smrti/                  # Python package
│   ├── __init__.py         # re-exports from memory
│   ├── __main__.py         # python -m smrti
│   ├── cli.py              # was smrti.py
│   ├── memory/             # unchanged internals
│   │   ├── __init__.py
│   │   ├── models.py
│   │   ├── storage.py
│   │   ├── tasks.py
│   │   ├── decisions.py
│   │   ├── facts.py
│   │   └── synthesis.py
│   ├── tools/              # utility scripts
│   │   ├── validate.py     # was validate_config.py
│   │   ├── export.py       # was export_docs.py
│   │   └── migrate.py      # was migrate_to_memory.py
│   └── apps/               # application code
│       ├── helper.py       # was sea_application_helper.py
│       └── assistant.py    # was sea_assistant.py
├── tests/
├── docs/
│   ├── rfcs/
│   ├── examples/           # was examples/ (configs)
│   ├── CONFIG.md
│   ├── WORKFLOW.md
│   └── EXAMPLES.md
├── LICENSE
├── README.md
├── pyproject.toml
└── .gitignore
@end example

GitHub shows 6 entries before README:
@code{smrti/}, @code{tests/}, @code{docs/}, @code{LICENSE}, @code{README.md}, @code{.gitignore}



@section What moves where


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Current @tab Proposed @tab Why
@item @code{memory/} @tab @code{smrti/memory/} @tab Inside the package
@item @code{smrti.py} @tab @code{smrti/cli.py} + @code{__main__.py} @tab Standard entry point
@item @code{sea_application_helper.py} @tab @code{smrti/apps/helper.py} @tab Application, not library
@item @code{sea_assistant.py} @tab @code{smrti/apps/assistant.py} @tab Application, not library
@item @code{validate_config.py} @tab @code{smrti/tools/validate.py} @tab Utility
@item @code{export_docs.py} @tab @code{smrti/tools/export.py} @tab Utility
@item @code{migrate_to_memory.py} @tab @code{smrti/tools/migrate.py} @tab One-time script
@item @code{config_schema.json} @tab @code{docs/config_schema.json} @tab Reference doc
@item @code{business_direction_analysis.md} @tab @code{docs/examples/} @tab Template
@item @code{examples/} @tab @code{docs/examples/} @tab Configs are docs by example
@item @code{CHANGELOG.md} @tab @code{docs/CHANGELOG.md} @tab History
@item @code{hooks/} @tab @code{.github/hooks/} @tab Convention
@end multitable



@section What stays


@multitable @columnfractions 0.50 0.50
@headitem File @tab Why
@item @code{README.md} @tab Required at root
@item @code{LICENSE} @tab Required at root
@item @code{CLAUDE.md} @tab Claude Code reads it from root
@item @code{.gitignore} @tab Required at root
@item @code{pyproject.toml} @tab New — replaces implicit setup
@end multitable




@section Packaging


@subsection pyproject.toml


@example
[project]
name = "advaita-smrti"
version = "0.5.0"
description = "Non-dual memory for structured knowledge elicitation"
license = "Apache-2.0"
requires-python = ">=3.6"
dependencies = []

[project.scripts]
smrti = "smrti.cli:main"

[build-system]
requires = ["hatchling"]
build-backend = "hatchling.build"
@end example

Zero dependencies. @code{pip install advaita-smrti} gives
you the @code{smrti} command.


@subsection PyPI name

@code{smrti} is taken (trivial package, 0.0.1 from 2019).
@code{advaita-smrti} is available. Use that.



@section Import changes


@example
# Before
from memory import Memory
from memory.models import Task, Fact

# After
from smrti.memory import Memory
from smrti.memory.models import Task, Fact

# Or via package re-export
from smrti import Memory, Fact
@end example

All internal imports within @code{smrti/memory/} stay relative
(no change). Only external consumers and tests change.



@section Migration


@subsection What breaks

@itemize @bullet
@item
Every @code{from memory import ...} in tests
@item
Every @code{from sea_application_helper import ...}
@item
@code{sys.path.insert(0, ...)} hacks in test files
@item
CI workflow paths
@item
Subtree prefix in day-shelter-kiosk (stays
  @code{advaita-smrti/} but internal paths change)
@item
CLAUDE.md code examples
@end itemize


@subsection Migration steps

@enumerate
@item
Create @code{smrti/} package with @code{__init__.py}
@item
Move @code{memory/} into @code{smrti/memory/}
@item
Move utility and application files
@item
Add @code{pyproject.toml}
@item
Update all imports (grep + sed)
@item
Update tests (remove sys.path hacks, use package imports)
@item
Update CI to install package (@code{pip install -e .})
@item
Update CLAUDE.md examples
@item
Run full test suite
@item
Pull into day-shelter-kiosk subtree
@end enumerate


@subsection Estimated touch count

~30 files. Same scale as the RFC 004 rename.



@section Open questions

@enumerate
@item
@strong{@code{sea_*} rename} — @code{helper.py} and @code{assistant.py}
   are generic enough. Or should they stay SEA-prefixed
   until there's a second application?
@item
@strong{@code{apps/} vs. @code{examples/}} — is the SEA application
   an example of using smrti, or a first-class app?
@item
@strong{Namespace package?} — should @code{smrti.memory} be
   importable standalone, or only through the top-level
   @code{smrti} package?
@item
@strong{When to do this} — before or after RFC 006 (web
   interface)? The web interface will add more files
   to the repo. Better to have the layout clean first.
@end enumerate



@section Decision: not yet

This RFC exists to capture the plan. Implementation is
deferred until one of:
@itemize @bullet
@item
PyPI publishing is needed
@item
RFC 006 (web interface) adds enough files to force it
@item
The top-level clutter becomes actively painful
@end itemize

The current layout works. It's just not pretty.



@node RFC 011
@chapter RFC 011: Tracer — Session Observation Layer


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Draft

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson + Claude

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-02-20

@noindent
@strong{Parent:} @strong{RFC 003}

@noindent
@strong{References:} @strong{RFC 002}, @strong{RFC 004}




@section Summary

Add a @strong{tracer} to smrti: a structured record of what happens
during a collaborative session. The tracer captures spans — units
of work performed by either participant (human or model) — and
organizes them into sessions. It is the observational layer that
RFC 003 proposed but did not specify.

The tracer answers: *what happened, who did it, and what did it
touch?*

The existing stores answer @emph{what} (tasks), @emph{why} (decisions), and
@emph{what is true} (facts). The tracer answers @emph{how} — the process by
which those stores were read, written, and connected during live
work.



@section Motivation


@subsection The gap in the memory layer

smrti has four memory types (RFC 004):


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Type @tab Records @tab Example
@item Procedural @tab What needs doing @tab "Answer Q4: short-term goals"
@item Episodic @tab What was decided @tab "Chose Flask over Django because..."
@item Semantic @tab What is known @tab "Shelter is on Ainsworth St"
@item Ephemeral @tab Active scratch @tab Draft answer in progress
@end multitable


None of these record @emph{the process itself}. After a session ends,
you can see that Q4 was answered, that a decision was made, that
a fact was created — but not @emph{how the session unfolded}. Which
questions were attempted and abandoned? Which facts were retrieved
but not used? Where did the human redirect the model? Where did
the model surface a connection the human hadn't seen?

RFC 003 proposed contribution tagging (P2) and session dimensions
(P4: momentum, reach, complementarity). Both require observational
data that doesn't exist yet. The tracer generates that data.


@subsection What the tracer is not

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Not a logger.} Logs are for debugging infrastructure. The
  tracer records cognitive collaboration, not API calls or stack
  traces.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Not an audit log.} Audit logs record @emph{who changed what} for
  accountability. The tracer records @emph{how work happened} for
  reflection. They overlap but serve different purposes and
  different audiences.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Not surveillance.} The tracer records what each participant
  @emph{contributed}, not how they @emph{behaved}. Time between actions is
  captured for momentum measurement (RFC 003 P4), not for
  monitoring productivity. See Privacy section.
@end itemize


@subsection The witness

In Advaita Vedānta, the @emph{sākṣin} (साक्षिन्) is the witness —
pure awareness that observes experience without altering it. The
tracer is the sākṣin of a session. It watches two minds work
together, records what each contributes, and holds that record
for later reflection.

The philosophical parallel is deliberate. The tool's namesake
tradition distinguishes between the actor (@emph{kartā}), the act
(@emph{kriyā}), and the witness (@emph{sākṣin}). The memory stores hold
the products of action. The tracer holds the witnessing of it.



@section Design


@subsection Core concepts

@strong{Session.} A bounded unit of collaborative work — one Claude
Code conversation, one interactive menu run, one queen's garden
sequence. Sessions have a start and end. A human may have
multiple sessions per day or one session spanning hours.

@strong{Span.} A unit of work within a session. Spans have a kind
(what type of work), an actor (who did it), a target (what it
touched), and a summary (what happened). Spans can nest: a
decision process is a parent span containing child spans for
each hypothesis, verification, and selection.

@strong{Actor.} Either @code{human} or @code{model}. The tracer does not
distinguish between different humans or different models — it
tracks the two participants in the collaboration.


@subsection Span kinds


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Kind @tab Actor @tab What it records
@item @code{input} @tab human @tab Human provided information, correction, or direction
@item @code{retrieve} @tab model @tab Model pulled data from a memory store
@item @code{draft} @tab model @tab Model composed or structured content
@item @code{refine} @tab either @tab Revision to existing content
@item @code{decide} @tab either @tab Selection among alternatives
@item @code{connect} @tab model @tab Model surfaced a cross-reference or dependency
@item @code{correct} @tab human @tab Human corrected a factual error
@item @code{redirect} @tab human @tab Human changed topic or approach
@item @code{check} @tab model @tab Coherence check or validation
@item @code{create} @tab either @tab New task, decision, or fact created
@item @code{close} @tab either @tab Task completed, decision finalized
@end multitable


This is not an exhaustive taxonomy — @code{metadata} carries anything
that doesn't fit. These kinds cover the patterns observed in
actual sessions (RFC 003's queen's garden analysis).


@subsection Relationship to existing stores

The tracer @emph{references} other stores but does not duplicate them.


@example
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Session sm-s-abc12                         │
│                                             │
│  span 1: retrieve  → task sm-7k2m4          │
│  span 2: input     → "budget and timeline"  │
│  span 3: draft     → answer for sm-7k2m4    │
│  span 4: connect   → sm-7k2m4 ↔ sm-9p3q1   │
│  span 5: correct   → "not $X, $Y"          │
│  span 6: refine    → updated answer          │
│  span 7: create    → fact sm-f-r8t2w         │
│  span 8: close     → task sm-7k2m4 closed   │
│                                             │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
@end example

The session tells a story. The spans are the sentences. The
existing stores hold the nouns (tasks, decisions, facts). The
tracer holds the verbs.



@section Data Model


@subsection Session


@example
@@dataclass
class Session:
    id: str                       # sm-s-xxxxx
    started_at: str               # ISO timestamp
    ended_at: Optional[str]       # ISO timestamp (null while active)
    mode: str                     # "garden" (continuous) or "wood" (per-question)
    summary: str                  # Post-session summary (generated at close)
    spans_count: int              # Number of spans in session
    tasks_touched: List[str]      # Task IDs read or written
    decisions_touched: List[str]  # Decision IDs read or written
    facts_touched: List[str]      # Fact IDs read or written
    metadata: Dict[str, Any]      # Extensible
@end example


@subsection Span


@example
@@dataclass
class Span:
    id: str                       # sm-t-xxxxx (t for trace)
    session_id: str               # Parent session
    kind: str                     # See span kinds table
    actor: str                    # "human" or "model"
    target: str                   # What was acted on (ID, path, or free text)
    summary: str                  # Brief description
    parent_span_id: Optional[str] # For nesting (nullable)
    seq: int                      # Ordering within session
    created_at: str               # ISO timestamp
    metadata: Dict[str, Any]      # Extensible (duration_ms, confidence, etc.)
@end example


@subsection IDs

@itemize @bullet
@item
Sessions: @code{sm-s-xxxxx} (s for session)
@item
Spans: @code{sm-t-xxxxx} (t for trace)
@end itemize

Following the existing convention of prefix + type marker +
5-char alphanumeric (RFC 004: @code{sm-f-xxxxx} for facts).



@section Storage


@subsection JSONL: @code{traces.jsonl}

Append-only, like the other stores. Each line is either a session
record or a span record, distinguished by the ID prefix (@code{sm-s-}
vs @code{sm-t-}).


@example
@{"id":"sm-s-abc12","started_at":"2026-02-20T09:00:00Z","mode":"garden","metadata":@{@}@}
@{"id":"sm-t-def34","session_id":"sm-s-abc12","kind":"retrieve","actor":"model","target":"sm-7k2m4","summary":"Loaded Q4 context","seq":1,"created_at":"2026-02-20T09:00:05Z","metadata":@{@}@}
@{"id":"sm-t-ghi56","session_id":"sm-s-abc12","kind":"input","actor":"human","target":"sm-7k2m4","summary":"Provided budget figure and timeline","seq":2,"created_at":"2026-02-20T09:01:30Z","metadata":@{@}@}
@end example


@subsection SQLite index additions


@example
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS sessions (
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    started_at TEXT,
    ended_at TEXT,
    mode TEXT,
    summary TEXT,
    spans_count INTEGER DEFAULT 0
);

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS spans (
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    session_id TEXT,
    kind TEXT,
    actor TEXT,
    target TEXT,
    summary TEXT,
    parent_span_id TEXT,
    seq INTEGER,
    created_at TEXT,
    FOREIGN KEY (session_id) REFERENCES sessions(id)
);

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS session_refs (
    session_id TEXT,
    ref_id TEXT,
    ref_type TEXT,  -- "task", "decision", "fact"
    PRIMARY KEY (session_id, ref_id)
);

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_spans_session ON spans(session_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_spans_kind ON spans(kind);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_spans_actor ON spans(actor);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_spans_target ON spans(target);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_session_refs_ref ON session_refs(ref_id);
@end example


@subsection Drift detection

Extends the existing pattern:


@example
Tasks:     JSONL has N, index has M
Decisions: JSONL has N, index has M
Facts:     JSONL has N, index has M
Traces:    JSONL has N sessions + M spans, index has N + M
@end example


@subsection Size management

Traces grow faster than other stores — a productive session
might generate 50–200 spans. Mitigation:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Compaction.} @code{mem.traces.compact()} deduplicates the JSONL,
   same as other stores.
@end enumerate

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Summarization.} At session close, generate a session summary
   and store it on the Session record. Individual spans can be
   queried when needed but the summary serves most review cases.
@end enumerate

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Archival.} Sessions older than a configurable threshold
   (default: 90 days) can be archived — their spans are removed
   from the index, the session record keeps its summary. Span
   data remains in the JSONL for forensic recovery.
@end enumerate



@section API


@subsection TracerStore


@example
mem = Memory(".memory", trace=True)

# --- Session lifecycle ---

session = mem.traces.begin(mode="garden")

mem.traces.span(
    session_id=session.id,
    kind="retrieve",
    actor="model",
    target="sm-7k2m4",
    summary="Loaded Q4 context and dependencies",
)

mem.traces.span(
    session_id=session.id,
    kind="input",
    actor="human",
    target="sm-7k2m4",
    summary="Provided budget figure: recurring cost",
)

# Nested spans
parent = mem.traces.span(
    session_id=session.id,
    kind="decide",
    actor="model",
    target="qt-abc12",
    summary="Evaluating framework options",
)
mem.traces.span(
    session_id=session.id,
    kind="draft",
    actor="model",
    target="qt-abc12",
    summary="Drafted hypothesis: Flask for speed",
    parent_span_id=parent.id,
)

mem.traces.end(session.id, summary="Completed Q4, created 2 facts")

# --- Queries ---

session = mem.traces.get_session(session_id)
spans = mem.traces.spans(session_id)
spans = mem.traces.spans(session_id, kind="input")
spans = mem.traces.spans(session_id, actor="human")
sessions = mem.traces.sessions(since="2026-02-01")
sessions = mem.traces.sessions(mode="garden")

# Timeline for a single target across sessions
timeline = mem.traces.timeline(target="sm-7k2m4")

# --- Derived metrics (RFC 003 P4) ---

metrics = mem.traces.metrics(session_id)
# Returns: @{ momentum: float, reach: float, complementarity: float @}

# --- Maintenance ---

mem.traces.compact()
mem.traces.archive(older_than_days=90)
@end example


@subsection Metrics derivation

The three metrics from RFC 003 P4 are computed from trace data:

@strong{Momentum.} Average time between consecutive spans, excluding
gaps longer than a threshold (default: 5 minutes, indicating the
human stepped away). Measured in seconds per span. Lower is
faster, but fast is not better — momentum is a flow indicator,
not a productivity score.

@strong{Reach.} Unique targets referenced across spans, divided by
total available tasks in the active config. A session that touches
15 of 49 questions has a reach of 0.31. Cross-references
(spans where @code{kind=connect}) are weighted higher because they
represent the integration work that distinguishes collaborative
answering from isolated answering.

@strong{Complementarity.} Ratio of human-originated spans to
model-originated spans, reported as a pair. A session with 40%
human / 60% model is @code{(0.4, 0.6)}. Extreme ratios suggest one
participant is carrying — the interpretation depends on context
(a financial section may legitimately need more model retrieval;
a personal narrative section may be mostly human input).


@subsection Integration with synthesis

The synthesis module gains access to trace data:


@example
# Pattern detection across sessions
patterns = mem.synthesize.session_patterns(since="2026-02-01")
# "Human corrections cluster around financial questions"
# "Model retrievals peak at section boundaries"

# Complementarity across sessions
comp = mem.synthesize.complementarity(session_id)
# @{ human_ratio: 0.45, model_ratio: 0.55, by_kind: @{...@} @}
@end example



@section Session Lifecycle


@subsection Automatic instrumentation

When an interactive workflow runs, the tracer starts a session
automatically. Key events are instrumented at the call sites:


@example
# In the interactive assistant
session = mem.traces.begin(mode="garden")

# When context is loaded
mem.traces.span(session.id, "retrieve", "model", task_id,
                "Loaded context")

# When the human speaks
mem.traces.span(session.id, "input", "human", task_id,
                "User provided budget details")

# When the model drafts
mem.traces.span(session.id, "draft", "model", task_id,
                "Drafted answer incorporating new data")

# When coherence check runs
mem.traces.span(session.id, "check", "model", section,
                "Section coherence check: 2 findings")

# At session end
mem.traces.end(session.id, summary=model_generated_summary)
@end example


@subsection Manual instrumentation

For users integrating smrti as a library, tracing is opt-in:


@example
mem = Memory(".memory", trace=True)    # Enable tracing
mem = Memory(".memory", trace=False)   # Disable (default)
@end example

When tracing is disabled, @code{mem.traces} is a no-op stub. All
@code{span()} and @code{begin()}/@code{end()} calls succeed silently and
return None. No performance cost when disabled.



@section CLI


@subsection @code{smrti.py memory traces}


@example
# List recent sessions
smrti.py memory traces
#   sm-s-abc12  2026-02-20 09:00  garden  42 spans  "Completed Q4, created 2 facts"
#   sm-s-def34  2026-02-19 14:30  wood    18 spans  "Answered Q15-Q17 financial section"

# Show spans for a session
smrti.py memory traces sm-s-abc12
