# Timeline for a target across sessions
smrti.py memory traces --target sm-7k2m4
@end example



@section Privacy


@subsection What the tracer records

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Span summaries} are brief descriptions of what happened,
  not transcripts. "User provided budget figure" is a span.
  The actual number lives in the task answer, not the trace.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Actor attribution} records @emph{which} participant, not *what
  they said*. The trace says "human corrected a fact" — the
  corrected fact lives in @code{facts.jsonl}.
@end itemize

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Timing} (via @code{created_at} on each span) enables momentum
  calculation. It does not record idle time, keystrokes, or
  attention metrics. The gap between spans is implicit; the
  tracer does not interpret it.
@end itemize


@subsection What the tracer does NOT record

@itemize @bullet
@item
Raw conversation text
@item
Keystrokes, mouse movements, or attention signals
@item
Time between spans as an explicit "idle" metric
@item
Model confidence scores or token probabilities
@item
PII beyond what the user explicitly provides as summaries
@end itemize


@subsection Data locality

Traces follow the same locality rules as the rest of smrti:
stored in @code{.memory/traces.jsonl}, never transmitted to external
services. The file may be gitignored in deployments where trace
data is considered sensitive.



@section Saṃcaya — Token Accounting


@subsection Motivation

The tracer (§Design) records @emph{what happened}. Token accounting
records @emph{what it cost}. Together they answer: how efficiently
did the collaboration proceed?

The existing stores and the tracer capture the @emph{shape} of
work. Token accounting captures the @emph{weight}. Without it, we
can say "the model drafted 12 answers" but not "at what cost
in tokens, and how did caching affect that cost?"


@subsection Data model: ApiCall

Every Anthropic API call made during a traced session is
recorded:


@example
@@dataclass
class ApiCall:
    id: str                          # sm-a-xxxxx
    session_id: str                  # links to tracer session
    span_id: Optional[str]           # links to tracer span
    task_id: Optional[str]           # what question was being worked on
    section: Optional[str]           # section grouping
    condition_id: Optional[str]      # experimental condition (harness mode)

    # From Anthropic usage object
    input_tokens: int                # prompt tokens (after cache)
    output_tokens: int               # output tokens (includes thinking)
    cache_creation_input_tokens: int
    cache_read_input_tokens: int

    # Derived
    total_input_tokens: int          # sum of all input categories
    effective_cost_units: float      # normalized cost (configurable ratios)

    model: str
    created_at: str
    seq: int                         # ordering within session
    metadata: dict
@end example


@subsection IDs

@code{sm-a-xxxxx} (a for api call). Follows the existing convention.


@subsection Effective Cost Units (ECU)

Different token types cost differently. ECU normalizes them
into a single comparable number using configurable ratios:


@example
ECU = (input_tokens × r_input)
    + (output_tokens × r_output)
    + (cache_creation_input_tokens × r_cache_create)
    + (cache_read_input_tokens × r_cache_read)
@end example

Default ratios (based on Anthropic Sonnet pricing, normalized
so @code{r_input = 1.0}):


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Token type @tab Default ratio @tab Why
@item @code{r_input} @tab 1.0 @tab baseline
@item @code{r_output} @tab 5.0 @tab output costs ~5× input
@item @code{r_cache_create} @tab 1.25 @tab 25% surcharge over input
@item @code{r_cache_read} @tab 0.1 @tab 90% discount from input
@end multitable


Ratios are stored in harness config and can be adjusted per
model. ECU is unit-free — it is a @emph{relative} cost measure for
comparison across conditions, not an absolute dollar figure.


@subsection Storage

@noindent
@strong{JSONL:} @code{apicalls.jsonl} — append-only, same pattern as

all other stores.

@noindent
@strong{SQLite index:} 



@example
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS apicalls (
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    session_id TEXT,
    span_id TEXT,
    task_id TEXT,
    section TEXT,
    condition_id TEXT,
    input_tokens INTEGER,
    output_tokens INTEGER,
    cache_creation_input_tokens INTEGER,
    cache_read_input_tokens INTEGER,
    total_input_tokens INTEGER,
    effective_cost_units REAL,
    model TEXT,
    created_at TEXT,
    seq INTEGER,
    FOREIGN KEY (session_id) REFERENCES sessions(id)
);

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_apicalls_session
    ON apicalls(session_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_apicalls_task
    ON apicalls(task_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_apicalls_condition
    ON apicalls(condition_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_apicalls_section
    ON apicalls(section);
@end example


@subsection Accumulation boundaries

Accumulators are @emph{queries}, not stored objects. Token totals
are computed on demand via SQL @code{GROUP BY}:


@example
-- Per task
SELECT task_id, SUM(effective_cost_units) AS ecu,
       SUM(total_input_tokens) AS input,
       SUM(output_tokens) AS output
FROM apicalls WHERE session_id = ? GROUP BY task_id;

-- Per section
SELECT section, SUM(effective_cost_units) AS ecu
FROM apicalls WHERE session_id = ? GROUP BY section;

-- Per condition (cross-session, for harness)
SELECT condition_id, SUM(effective_cost_units) AS ecu,
       COUNT(*) AS api_calls
FROM apicalls GROUP BY condition_id;
@end example


@subsection Key design decisions

@itemize @bullet
@item
Record at the API call level, accumulate on demand
@item
No separate accumulator records — keep storage simple
@item
ECU normalizes across token types for fair comparison
@item
Opt-in: only active when @code{trace=True} on Memory init
@item
No new dependencies: @code{sqlite3} + stdlib only
@end itemize



@section Pramāṇa — Measurement Harness


@subsection Purpose

A controlled experiment mode for comparing collaboration
efficiency across memory configurations. The harness runs the
same question set under different avasthās (conditions) and
records everything needed for analysis.


@subsection Six Avasthās (Experimental Conditions)


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem ID @tab Name @tab Memory configuration
@item C0 @tab Baseline @tab No smrti — all context in prompt
@item C1 @tab Procedural @tab Tasks store only
@item C2 @tab Proc + Episodic @tab Tasks + decisions
@item C3 @tab All stores @tab Tasks + decisions + facts
@item C4 @tab + Coherence @tab C3 + cross-answer validation
@item C5 @tab Full @tab C4 + dependency-aware retrieval
@end multitable


The conditions form an ablation study: each adds one
capability to the previous. This isolates the marginal
contribution of each memory type.


@subsection InstrumentedClient

A wrapper around the Anthropic client that intercepts API
responses and records token usage:


@example
class InstrumentedClient:
    """Wraps anthropic.Client to record token usage."""

    def __init__(self, client, tracer, session_id, condition_id=None):
        self.client = client
        self.tracer = tracer
        self.session_id = session_id
        self.condition_id = condition_id

    def messages_create(self, **kwargs):
        response = self.client.messages.create(**kwargs)
        self.tracer.record_api_call(
            session_id=self.session_id,
            usage=response.usage,
            model=response.model,
            condition_id=self.condition_id,
            metadata=@{"task_id": kwargs.get("metadata", @{@}).get("task_id")@},
        )
        return response
@end example

No subclassing, no monkey-patching. The instrumented client
is composed, not inherited. Consumer code passes it where
it would pass the raw client.


@subsection Harness config


@example
@{
  "harness": @{
    "conditions": ["C0", "C1", "C2", "C3", "C4", "C5"],
    "question_set": "questions_harness.json",
    "ordering": "fixed",
    "seed_data": @{
      "facts": "seed/facts.jsonl",
      "decisions": "seed/decisions.jsonl"
    @},
    "cost_ratios": @{
      "r_input": 1.0,
      "r_output": 5.0,
      "r_cache_create": 1.25,
      "r_cache_read": 0.1
    @},
    "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
    "temperature": 0.0
  @}
@}
@end example


@subsection Harness runner


@example
class HarnessRunner:
    """Runs a question set under a single avasthā."""

    def __init__(self, config, condition_id, memory_path):
        self.config = config
        self.condition_id = condition_id
        self.mem = self._init_memory(condition_id, memory_path)

    def _init_memory(self, condition_id, path):
        """Configure memory stores per condition."""
        if condition_id == "C0":
            return None  # no memory
        mem = Memory(path, trace=True)
        # C1: only tasks; C2: tasks + decisions; etc.
        # Store availability controlled by condition
        return mem

    def run(self, questions):
        session = self.mem.traces.begin(
            mode="wood",
            metadata=@{"condition": self.condition_id@}
        )
        for q in questions:
            self._answer_question(session, q)
        self.mem.traces.end(session.id)
@end example


@subsection Key constraint

No new dependencies. Pure Python + stdlib + sqlite3. The
harness is part of smrti, not a separate tool.



@section Vivecana — Export and Analysis


@subsection Purpose

Export trace and token data in analysis-ready formats for
pandas, R, or any statistics tool.


@subsection Export formats

@noindent
@strong{CSV:} One row per API call, with session, task, section,

condition, and all token fields. Ready for @code{pd.read_csv()}.


@example
api_call_id,session_id,condition_id,task_id,section,input_tokens,output_tokens,cache_creation,cache_read,total_input,ecu,model,created_at
sm-a-abc12,sm-s-def34,C3,sm-7k2m4,financial,1200,450,0,800,2000,3650.0,claude-sonnet-4-6,2026-02-21T10:00:00Z
@end example

@noindent
@strong{JSON:} Nested structure with session-level summaries and

per-task breakdowns. For programmatic consumption.


@example
@{
  "export_version": "1.0",
  "conditions": @{
    "C3": @{
      "sessions": 3,
      "total_ecu": 45200.0,
      "total_api_calls": 127,
      "tasks": @{
        "sm-7k2m4": @{
          "ecu": 3650.0,
          "api_calls": 8,
          "quality_score": null
        @}
      @}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example


@subsection CLI


@example
# Export all trace + token data as CSV
smrti.py harness export --format csv > results.csv

# Export summaries per condition
smrti.py harness export --format json --summary > summary.json

# Export a single session
smrti.py harness export --session sm-s-abc12 --format csv
@end example


@subsection Quality scores

Quality is assessed externally (human rater, blind to
condition) and merged into the export:


@example
# Import quality scores from a rubric file
smrti.py harness quality-import rubric_scores.csv

# rubric_scores.csv format:
# task_id,condition_id,completeness,specificity,coherence,actionability,integration
# sm-7k2m4,C3,4,5,3,4,5
@end example

Once imported, artha (ECU per quality-point) can be computed.



@section Artha — Economy Metric


@subsection The fourth dimension

RFC 003 P4 proposed three session metrics: momentum, reach,
and complementarity. Token accounting enables a fourth:

@strong{Economy (artha).} ECU per quality-point — how many
effective cost units does it take to produce one unit of
assessed quality?


@example
artha = total_ecu / mean_quality_score
@end example

Lower artha means more efficient collaboration: less token
spend per unit of quality. The metric is meaningful only when
comparing across conditions with the same question set and
quality rubric.


@subsection Interpretation


@multitable @columnfractions 0.50 0.50
@headitem artha @tab Interpretation
@item Low, stable @tab Efficient collaboration. Memory is working.
@item High, declining across conditions @tab Memory is reducing cost progressively.
@item Low C0, rising with memory @tab Memory adds overhead without quality gain.
@item High everywhere @tab Hard question set or inefficient model usage.
@end multitable


Artha is not a standalone score. It is comparative — it
answers: *does adding this memory capability improve the
cost-quality ratio?*


@subsection The four dimensions together


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Metric @tab Question it answers @tab Source
@item Momentum @tab How fast is the session flowing? @tab Span timestamps
@item Reach @tab How much of the question set was touched? @tab Span targets
@item Complementarity @tab Who contributed what? @tab Span actors
@item Economy (artha) @tab How efficient is the collaboration? @tab Token accounting + quality rubric
@end multitable




@section Research Protocol


@subsection Quality rubric

Five dimensions, each scored 1–5 by a human rater blind to
experimental condition:


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Dimension @tab 1 (low) @tab 5 (high)
@item Completeness @tab Major gaps @tab All parts addressed
@item Specificity @tab Generic, no details @tab Concrete numbers, dates, examples
@item Coherence @tab Contradicts other answers @tab Consistent across section
@item Actionability @tab Vague intentions @tab Clear next steps
@item Integration @tab Ignores related questions @tab References and builds on related answers
@end multitable


Mean quality score = arithmetic mean of the five dimensions.


@subsection Statistical plan

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Primary comparison:} ECU across C0–C5 for the same
  question set
@item
@strong{Secondary comparison:} Quality scores across conditions
@item
@strong{Derived:} Artha (ECU/quality) across conditions
@item
@strong{Minimum sessions:} 3 per condition (18 total) for
  variance estimation
@item
@strong{Analysis:} Paired comparison (same questions across
  conditions eliminates question-difficulty confound)
@item
@strong{Reporting:} Effect sizes with confidence intervals;
  no p-value thresholds without pre-registration
@end itemize


@subsection Threats to validity

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Internal:} Model behavior may vary across runs even at
  temperature 0 (sampling is not fully deterministic)
@item
@strong{Construct:} ECU is a proxy for cost, not actual cost
  (ratios are approximate)
@item
@strong{External:} Results from one question set / one domain
  may not generalize
@item
@strong{Rater bias:} Single rater introduces subjectivity;
  mitigated by blind-to-condition scoring
@end itemize



@section Sanskrit Lexicon

Terms used in this RFC and their philosophical grounding:


@multitable @columnfractions 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25
@headitem Sanskrit @tab Devanagari @tab Meaning @tab Maps to
@item kartā @tab कर्तृ @tab the doer, agent @tab Actor (human or model)
@item kriyā @tab क्रिया @tab the act, deed @tab Span (unit of work)
@item sākṣin @tab साक्षिन् @tab the witness @tab Tracer itself
@item saṃcaya @tab संचय @tab accumulation, gathering @tab Token accumulator
@item pramāṇa @tab प्रमाण @tab valid means of knowledge @tab Measurement harness
@item artha @tab अर्थ @tab purpose, economy @tab Economy metric (ECU/quality)
@item satra @tab सत्र @tab session, prolonged ceremony @tab Session
@item avasthā @tab अवस्था @tab state, condition @tab Experimental condition
@item vivecana @tab विवेचन @tab discernment, analysis @tab Export/analysis
@item pratītya @tab प्रतीत्य @tab in dependence on @tab Interbeing (co-arising)
@item sahaja @tab सहज @tab co-born, arising together @tab Interbeing (short form)
@end multitable


The naming follows Advaita Vedānta's analysis of action
(kartā–kriyā–sākṣin) and Indian epistemology's theory of
valid knowledge (pramāṇa). See @code{docs/papers/bibliography.bib}
entries @code{deutsch1969advaita} and @code{mohanty2000classical}.



