@node RFC 013
@chapter RFC 013: smṛti-bench — Rationale and Design


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Implemented

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-03-18

@noindent
@strong{Parent:} @strong{RFC 004}



@section Purpose

Document why smṛti-bench exists, what it measures, and how the
scoring system works.



@section Problem

AI agents start every session from zero. They can read the codebase,
but they have no record of decisions made, rationale behind choices,
task status, or deferred work. When asked "why did we choose
Supabase?", an agent without memory either admits ignorance or
hallucinates a plausible answer.

smrti gives agents persistent structured memory via MCP. But
"persistent memory" is only valuable if it actually improves
responses. smṛti-bench measures whether it does.


@section What we test

The bench runs a battery of 6 prompts against a seeded fixture —
a fake Flutter project ("trellis") with facts, decisions, and tasks
stored across smrti's three typed stores.

Each prompt targets a different memory capability:


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem Prompt @tab Tests @tab Store exercised
@item PROMPT_01 @tab Fact recall (project name, language) @tab Semantic (facts)
@item PROMPT_02 @tab Decision rationale (why Supabase over Firebase) @tab Episodic (decisions)
@item PROMPT_03 @tab Task status (what's open vs closed) @tab Procedural (tasks)
@item PROMPT_04 @tab Coherence (consistent with prior decisions) @tab Episodic (decisions)
@item PROMPT_05 @tab Deferred recall (why offline sync was deferred) @tab Episodic (decisions)
@item PROMPT_06 @tab Hallucination trap (ORM not in memory) @tab Absence detection
@end multitable



@section Two arms

@strong{Baseline} — agent runs in an empty directory with no memory tools.
Correct behavior: admit ignorance. Pass = no hallucination.

@strong{smrti} — agent has MCP tools connected to the seeded fixture.
Correct behavior: query memory stores and answer accurately.
Pass = expected keywords present, no traps triggered.


@section Three platforms

The same battery runs against Claude Code, Gemini (API), and
Antigravity. This tests whether the MCP memory layer works
across different agent platforms, not just one.


@section Scoring: ASP (Answer Set Programming)

Python extracts text predicates from each response (keyword
presence, ignorance signals, assertion phrases). Clingo
evaluates declarative rules to derive grades.

Three rule sets:


@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem File @tab Scope @tab Purpose
@item @code{scoring.lp} @tab Per-prompt @tab Grade derivation + integrity constraints
@item @code{coherence.lp} @tab Per-run (all prompts) @tab Cross-prompt consistency checks
@item @code{regression.lp} @tab Cross-run @tab Detect regressions between consecutive runs
@end multitable



@subsection Why ASP over Python

The grading logic involves negation ("pass if NOT missing keywords
AND NOT trap triggered AND NOT error"), excuse chains ("hallucination
is excused IF admits ignorance AND no assertions"), and cross-prompt
reasoning ("contradiction if pass on P1 but fail on P2"). These are
natural in ASP and awkward in imperative code. The @code{.lp} files also
serve as a readable specification of what "correct" means.


@section Fixture design

The fixture is intentionally non-trivial:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Architecture answers (PROMPT_02, PROMPT_04) live @strong{only} in the
  decisions store — not duplicated in facts. The agent must use
  @code{decision_list} / @code{decision_get}, not just @code{fact_search}.
@item
The deferral rationale (PROMPT_05) lives in a decision with no
  explicit @code{task_id} link. The task (PROMPT_03) says "deferred to v0.3"
  but not why. Full answer requires cross-store synthesis.
@item
Noise facts (team conventions, MVP timeline, rate limiting) and
  a noise task (analytics evaluation) test filtering.
@item
PROMPT_06 tests absence — the ORM fact is intentionally missing.
  Naming any ORM is a hallucination failure.
@end itemize


@section What success looks like

@itemize @bullet
@item
Baseline: 6/6 PASS (never hallucinates project-specific content)
@item
smrti: 6/6 PASS (recalls accurately from all three stores)
@item
No coherence warnings (consistent across related prompts)
@item
No regressions between runs
@end itemize


@section Future work

@itemize @bullet
@item
@strong{Weighted run scores} — @code{#minimize} to rank runs by quality
  when the prompt battery grows beyond 6
@item
@strong{UNSURE decomposition} — choice rules to classify ambiguous
  responses instead of a catch-all grade
@end itemize



@node RFC 017
@chapter RFC 017: Multilingual Grounding Fidelity


@noindent
@strong{Status:} Hypothesis

@noindent
@strong{Author:} Aaron Johnson

@noindent
@strong{Created:} 2026-03-18

@noindent
@strong{Parent:} @strong{RFC 013}



@section Hypothesis

Grounding fidelity — the degree to which an agent's responses are
faithfully attributed to structured memory — varies by human language
for the same model. Models may be more prone to unattributed
assertions in languages with less training data.


@section Background

RFC 013 established smṛti-bench and the five-level grounding fidelity
spectrum:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Grounded recall} — answers from memory (PASS)
@item
@strong{Grounded absence} — correctly says "not in memory" (PASS)
@item
@strong{Helpful elaboration} — general knowledge, disclaimed (PASS)
@item
@strong{Unattributed assertion} — project claim without source (FAIL)
@item
@strong{Confabulation} — invented project history (FAIL)
@end enumerate

The current scorer uses English phrase lists to classify agent
behavior on this spectrum. The ASP rules that derive grades from
those classifications are language-independent.


@section Key Insight

The architecture separates @strong{perception} (Python phrase extraction)
from @strong{judgement} (ASP rules). This separation is validated by the
multilingual case: the judgement logic (@code{scoring.lp}, @code{coherence.lp},
@code{regression.lp}) doesn't change across languages. Only the perception
layer needs locale-specific variants.


@section What Would Change

@strong{Locale-specific phrase lists} (Python):


@example
# English (existing)
MEMORY_CITATION_PHRASES = ["according to memory", "decision qt-", ...]
GENERAL_KNOWLEDGE_PHRASES = ["common choices", "typically", ...]

# Japanese (new)
MEMORY_CITATION_PHRASES_JA = ["メモリによると", "decision qt-", ...]
GENERAL_KNOWLEDGE_PHRASES_JA = ["一般的には", "よく使われるのは", ...]
@end example

@strong{Translated fixture and prompts} — the "trellis" project scenario
and 6-prompt battery in the target language.

@strong{ASP rules} — no changes.


@section What Would Not Change

@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{scoring.lp} — grade derivation, integrity constraints, attribution rules
@item
@code{coherence.lp} — cross-prompt consistency checks
@item
@code{regression.lp} — cross-run comparison
@item
The grounding fidelity spectrum itself
@end itemize


@section Open Questions

@itemize @bullet
@item
Which languages first? Japanese (日本語) is the initial candidate.
@item
Do we test the same models, or include models with stronger
  non-English training (e.g., Japanese-specialized models)?
@item
Is the five-level spectrum sufficient, or do some languages
  have discourse patterns that don't map cleanly?
@item
How do we handle mixed-language responses (code-switching)?
@end itemize


@section Implications

If grounding fidelity varies by language, this affects which models
are safe to deploy with structured memory in non-English contexts.
A model that correctly attributes in English but confabulates in
Japanese would need different guardrails per locale.


@bye
